46''' \u2013 Manchester United\n*Fewest goals scored: '''10''' \u2013 Manchester City\n*Most goals conceded: '''30''' \u2013 Wigan Athletic\n*Fewest goals conceded: '''7''' \u2013 Liverpool\n\n===Away===\n*Most wins: '''13''' \u2013 Manchester United\n*Fewest wins: '''1''' \u2013 Fulham and Charlton Athletic\n*Most losses: '''14''' \u2013 Sheffield United\n*Fewest losses: '''3''' \u2013 Manchester United and Chelsea\n*Most goals scored: '''37''' \u2013 Manchester United\n*Fewest goals scored: '''8''' \u2013 Sheffield United\n*Most goals conceded: '''42''' \u2013 Fulham\n*Fewest goals conceded: '''13''' \u2013 Chelsea\n\n==Statistics==\n\n===Goals===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Rank\n!Scorer\n!Club\n!Goals\n|-\n|align=center|1\n|{{flagicon|CIV}} [[Didier Drogba]]\n|Chelsea\n|align=center|20\n|-\n|align=center|2\n|{{flagicon|ZAF}} [[Benni McCarthy]]\n|Blackburn Rovers\n|align=center|18\n|-\n|align=center|3\n|{{flagicon|POR}} [[Cristiano Ronaldo]]\n|Manchester United\n|align=center|17\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=center|4\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Wayne Rooney]]\n|Manchester United\n|align=center|14\n|-\n|{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Mark Viduka]]\n|Middlesbrough\n|align=center|14\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=center|6\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Darren Bent]]\n|Charlton Athletic\n|align=center|13\n|-\n|{{flagicon|IRL}} [[Kevin Doyle]]\n|Reading\n|align=center|13\n|-\n|rowspan=3 align=center|8\n|{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Dimitar Berbatov]]\n|Tottenham Hotspur\n|align=center|12\n|-\n|{{flagicon|NLD}} [[Dirk Kuyt]]\n|Liverpool\n|align=center|12\n|-\n|{{flagicon|NGA}} [[Yakubu (footballer)|Yakubu]]\n|Middlesbrough\n|align=center|12\n|-\n|}\n\n===Historic goals===\n====15,000th goal====\nThe Premier League expected to have the league's 15,000th goal scored at some point in the period between Christmas and New Year. The target was reached on 30 December when [[Moritz Volz]] scored for Fulham against Chelsea. [[Barclays]], the Premiership's sponsor, donated \u00a315,000 to the Fulham Community Sports Trust in Volz' name.  Additionally, a fan who correctly predicted that Volz would score the historic goal in a contest presented the player with a special award prior to Fulham's game against Watford at [[Craven Cottage]] on 1 January.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.premierleague.com/fapl.rac?command=setSelectedId&nextPage=enNewsLatest&id=1572495&type=com.fapl.website.news.NewsItem&categoryCode=NewsSpecialFeatures |title=VOLZ SCORES 15,000TH PREMIER LEAGUE GOAL |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070123083417/http://www.premierleague.com/fapl.rac?command=setSelectedId&nextPage=enNewsLatest&id=1572495&type=com.fapl.website.news.NewsItem&categoryCode=NewsSpecialFeatures |archivedate=23 January 2007 |publisher=premierleague.com |date=30 December 2006 |accessdate=17 May 2007 }}</ref> The honour of scoring the 15,000th goal led to Volz being nicknamed \"15,000 Volz\".{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\n====Goalkeeper scores====\nOn 17 March 2007, Tottenham Hotspur [[goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] [[Paul Robinson (goalkeeper)|Paul Robinson]] scored against Watford from an 83-yard free kick, which bounced over his [[England national football team|England]] teammate [[Ben Foster (footballer)|Ben Foster]], who was in goal for the Hornets, leading Spurs to a 3\u20131 win at [[White Hart Lane]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/6437237.stm |title=Tottenham 3\u20131 Watford |publisher=BBC Sport |date=17 March 2007 |accessdate=17 May 2007 |first=Sam |last=Lyon}}</ref> This was the third goal scored by a goalkeeper in Premiership history. The other two were scored by [[Peter Schmeichel]], for Aston Villa against Everton on 21 October 2001,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/1606115.stm |title=Schmeichel strike in vain |publisher=BBC Sport |date=20 October 2001 |accessdate=17 May 2007 }}</ref> and [[Brad Friedel]], for Blackburn Rovers against Charlton Athletic on 21 February 2004.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/3496741.stm |title=Charlton 3\u20132 Blackburn |publisher=BBC Sport |date=21 February 2004 |accessdate=17 May 2007 }}</ref> In those two cases, the teams they played for lost. Robinson became the first keeper to score for the winning team in a Premiership match.\n\n==Relegation controversy==\n[[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]] escaped relegation on the final day of the season with a 1\u20130 win over [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], with [[Carlos Tevez]] scoring the winner.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nurse |first1=Howard |title=Man Utd 0-1 West Ham |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/6627803.stm |accessdate=3 January 2019 |work=BBC Sport |date=13 May 2007}}</ref> [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] were relegated, along with [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton]] and [[Watford F.C.|Watford]]. Tevez was subsequently found to have been ineligible to play, as he was not owned by West Ham, but by a third party. Sheffield United sued to keep their Premier League status and, when that failed, went to an FA arbitration panel seeking up to \u00a330m compensation. The arbitration panel found in favour of Sheffield.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dollard |first1=Rory |title=Sheffield Utd win ruling against West Ham over Tevez |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/sheffield-utd-win-ruling-against-west-ham-over-tevez-939361.html |accessdate=3 January 2019 |work=The Independent |date=23 September 2008}}</ref> The two clubs subsequently settled out of court for an undisclosed sum.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kelso |first1=Paul |title=West Ham and Sheffield United reach out-of-court settlement over Carlos Tevez affair |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/premier-league/4981170/West-Ham-and-Sheffield-United-reach-out-of-court-settlement-over-Carlos-Tevez-affair.html |accessdate=3 January 2019 |work=The Telegraph |date=13 March 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Monthly awards==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!Month!![[Premier League Manager of the Month|Manager]]!![[Premier League Player of the Month|Player]]\n|-\n|August 2006||[[Alex Ferguson|Sir Alex Ferguson]] (Manchester United)||[[Ryan Giggs]] (Manchester United)\n|-\n|September 2006||[[Steve Coppell]] (Reading)||[[Andrew Johnson (English footballer)|Andrew Johnson]] (Everton)\n|-\n|October 2006||[[Alex Ferguson|Sir Alex Ferguson]] (Manchester United)||[[Paul Scholes]] (Manchester United)\n|-\n|November 2006|| [[Steve Coppell]] (Reading) || [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] (Manchester United)\n|-\n|December 2006|| [[Sam Allardyce]] ([[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton]]) || [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] (Manchester United)\n|-\n|January 2007|| [[Rafael Ben\u00edtez]] (Liverpool) || [[Cesc F\u00e0bregas]] (Arsenal)\n|-\n|February 2007|| [[Alex Ferguson|Sir Alex Ferguson]] (Manchester United) || [[Ryan Giggs]] (Manchester United)\n|-\n|March 2007|| [[Jos\u00e9 Mourinho]] (Chelsea) || [[Petr \u010cech]] (Chelsea) \n|-\n|April 2007|| [[Martin O'Neill]] (Aston Villa) || [[Robbie Keane]] (Tottenham Hotspur)<br />[[Dimitar Berbatov]] (Tottenham Hotspur){{efn|[[Robbie Keane|Keane]] and [[Dimitar Berbatov|Berbatov]] became the first joint winners of the Player of the Month award since Arsenal's [[Dennis Bergkamp]] and [[Edu (footballer, born 1978)|Edu]] in February 2004</small><ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/6631841.stm | title = Keane & Berbatov win April award | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 7 May 2007 | accessdate =17 May 2007 }}</ref>}}\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Annual awards==\nThis season's awards were dominated by Manchester United, who, as a team, picked up a total of eight individual awards, five of which went to [[Cristiano Ronaldo]]. They also had eight players in the Team of the Year.\n\n===PFA Players' Player of the Year===\nThe [[PFA Players' Player of the Year]] award for 2007 was won by [[Cristiano Ronaldo]]. He had won the PFA Young Player of the Year award earlier on in the awards ceremony, making him the first player to win both awards in the same year since [[Andy Gray (commentator)|Andy Gray]] managed the same feat in 1977. Didier Drogba came second, while Paul Scholes was third.\n\nThe shortlist for the PFA Players' Player of the Year award, in alphabetical order, is as follows:\n*[[Didier Drogba]] (Chelsea)\n*[[Cesc F\u00e0bregas]] (Arsenal)\n*[[Steven Gerrard]] (Liverpool)\n*[[Ryan Giggs]] (Manchester United)\n*[[Cristiano Ronaldo]] (Manchester United)\n*[[Paul Scholes]] (Manchester United)\n\n===PFA Young Player of the Year===\nThe [[PFA Young Player of the Year]] award was also won by [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] of Manchester United. Cesc F\u00e0bregas came in second place, and Aaron Lennon was third. Wayne Rooney was going for a hat-trick of Young Player of the Year awards, having won this award for both of the two preceding seasons, but didn't even feature in the top three for the 2006\u201307 season.\n\nThe shortlist for the award was as follows:\n*[[Kevin Doyle]] (Reading)\n*[[Cesc F\u00e0bregas]] (Arsenal)\n*[[Aaron Lennon]] (Tottenham Hotspur)\n*[[Micah Richards]] ([[Manchester City F.C.|Man City]])\n*[[Cristiano Ronaldo]] (Manchester United)\n*[[Wayne Rooney]] (Manchester United)\n\n===PFA Team of the Year===\nGoalkeeper: [[Edwin van der Sar]] (Manchester United)<br />\nDefence: [[Gary Neville]], [[Patrice Evra]], [[Rio Ferdinand]], [[Nemanja Vidi\u0107]] (all Manchester United)<br />\nMidfield: [[Steven Gerrard]] (Liverpool), [[Paul Scholes]], [[Ryan Giggs]], [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] (all Manchester United)<br />\nAttack: [[Didier Drogba]] (Chelsea), [[Dimitar Berbatov]] (Tottenham Hotspur)\n\n===PFA Merit Award===\nThe PFA Merit Award was awarded to [[Alex Ferguson|Sir Alex Ferguson]], manager of Manchester United, for his commitment to the club, the Premiership, and as recognition of the nineteen major trophies he has won in his time in England.\n\n===PFA Fans' Player of the Year===\nThis award was voted for in an online poll run by the PFA on their website. With four days of voting left before the closing date of midnight on 15 April, the five players with the most votes in the poll were [[Cristiano Ronaldo]], [[Steven Gerrard]], [[Dimitar Berbatov]], [[Thierry Henry]] and [[Frank Lampard]], but it was Ronaldo who managed to fend off the challenges of the other four.\n\n===FWA Footballer of the Year===\nThe [[FWA Footballer of the Year]] award for 2007 was also won by Cristiano Ronaldo. The award is presented by the [[Football Writers' Association]] and voted for by its members. This year, Didier Drogba came second and Ryan Giggs and Paul Scholes came third and fourth respectively.\n\n===Premier League Manager of the Season===\nThe [[Premier League Manager of the Season]] award was presented to Manchester United's [[Alex Ferguson|Sir Alex Ferguson]] before the club's final game of the season against West Ham United.\n\n===Premier League Player of the Season===\nThe [[Premier League Player of the Season]] award was also presented before Manchester United's game with West Ham United on the last day of the season, and was awarded to [[Cristiano Ronaldo]], granting him the sextuple of PFA Players' Player, Young Player, Fans' Player of the Year, Barclays Premiership Player of the Season, Football Writers' Association Player of the Year and a place in the Team of the Year.\n\n===Premier League Merit Award===\n[[Ryan Giggs]] was presented with this special award at the same time as the Manager and Player of the Season Awards were given out, in recognition of his record of nine Premier League titles.\n\n===Premier League Golden Glove===\nThe [[Premier League Golden Glove]] award was presented to Liverpool's [[Pepe Reina]] for the second successive season after keeping 19 clean sheets, ahead of [[Tim Howard]] of Everton (14) and [[Marcus Hahnemann]] of Reading (13).<ref>{{cite web|title=REINA NETS GOALKEEPING AWARD |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/latest-news/reina-nets-goalkeeping-award |accessdate=2 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006113019/http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/latest-news/reina-nets-goalkeeping-award |archivedate=6 October 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n==See also==\n*[[2006\u201307 in English football]]\n*[[2006\u201307 Football League]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/eng07.html 2006\u201307 Premier League Season at RSSSF]\n* Premier League 2006\u201307 on BBC Sport: <span class=\"plainlinks\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/ News] \u2013 [http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/results/ Recent results] \u2013 [http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/fixtures/ Upcoming fixtures] \u2013 [http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/live_scores/ Live Scores] \u2013 [http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/table/ Current standings]</span>\n*[http://www.premierleague.com/ Official Premier League site]\n\n{{Premier League}}\n{{2006-07 in English football}}\n{{2006-07 in European Football (UEFA)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2006-07 FA Premier League}}\n[[Category:2006\u201307 FA Premier League| ]]\n[[Category:Premier League seasons]]\n[[Category:2006\u201307 in European association football leagues|Eng]]\n[[Category:2006\u201307 in English football leagues|1]]\n", "name_user": "KoSpades", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGoals", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2006%E2%80%9307_FA_Premier_League"}
{"title_page": "Weebill", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| name              = Weebill\n| image             = Weebill Smicrornis brevirostris) 12 September 2015 Cropped.jpg\n| image_caption     = Nominate subspecies, Victoria\n| status            = LC\n| status_system     = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref        = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704662/0 |title=''Smicrornis brevirostris'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus             = Smicrornis\n| parent_authority  = [[John Gould|Gould]], 1843\n| species           = brevirostris\n| authority         = ([[John Gould (ornithologist)|Gould]], 1838)\n| range_map         = Weebill_distribution.png\n| range_map_caption = Approximate range in Australia\n{{Leftlegend|#FF0000|Year-round range|outline=gray}}\n}}\n\nThe '''weebill''' (''Smicrornis brevirostris'') is a species of bird in the family [[Acanthizidae]], it is an [[Insectivore|insectivorous]] [[passerine]] that is found throughout mainland [[Australia]]. At {{convert|8|to|9|cm|in|abbr=on}} long, it is Australia's smallest bird. It was originally described by [[John Gould]] in 1838, and four subspecies are recognised. The weebill's plumage is nondescript, with olive-grey upperparts and paler, more yellowish underparts. It grades from more brownish plumage in the southern regions of Australia to more yellow in tropical areas.\n\n== Taxonomy ==\nThe weebill was described by John Gould in 1838 as ''Psilopus brevirostris''. The species epithet is derived from the [[Latin]] words ''brevis'' 'short' and ''rostrum'' 'beak'.<ref name=fraser13>{{cite book|last1=Gray|first1=Jeannie|last2=Fraser|first2=Ian|title=Australian Bird Names: A Complete Guide|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=W1TCqHVWQp0C&pg=PT184|year=2013|publisher=CSIRO Publishing|location=Collingwood, Victoria | isbn=978-0-643-10471-6|page=184}}</ref>\n\nIn 1843, Gould erected the genus ''Smicrornis'' for his new species ''Smicrornis flavescens'', collected from Port Essington, noting it as distinct from ''[[Gerygone]]'' (which had replaced ''Psilopus as a ''name'').<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gould |first1=John |title=Proceedings of meeting of Zoological Society of London, Oct. 11, 1842 |journal=Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London |date=1842 |volume=10 |pages=131\u2013140 [133\u2013134] |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/30679895}}</ref>'' The generic name ''Smicrornis'' derives from the Greek ''smicros'' 'small' and ''ornis'' 'bird'.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling|title=Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird-names|last=Jobling|first=James A.|accessdate = 2020-04-17}}</ref> It is the [[Monotypic taxon|only member]] of genus ''Smicrornis''; [[gene flow]] is strong and local variation follows [[Bergmann's rule|Bergmann's]] and [[Gloger's rule|Gloger's]] rules.<ref name=\"keast1958\">{{cite journal |last1=Keast |first1=Allan |title=Geographic variation in the Weebill, Smicrornis brevirostris (Gould) (Passeres: Muscicapidae, malurinae) a sedentary species with a continuous range |journal=Australian Journal of Zoology |date=1958 |volume=6 |issue=2 |pages=152\u2013161 |doi=10.1071/ZO9580152}}</ref><ref name=ALA>{{Cite web|url=https://bie.ala.org.au/species/urn:lsid:biodiversity.org.au:afd.taxon:e2e2e858-5403-4981-8baf-b5202275fa7a|title=Smicrornis brevirostris : Weebill|last=Australia|first=Atlas of Living|website=bie.ala.org.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref>\n\nGould initially called it the short-billed smicrornis, but it did not gain acceptance. Other names include tree-tit, short billed tree-tit, scrub-tit, or short-billed scrub-tit. Weebill was adopted as the name in the 1926 RAOU checklist.<ref name=fraser13/>\n\n=== Subspecies ===\nFour [[subspecies]] are currently recognised in addition to the nominate subspecies:<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n* S. ''b''. ''flavescens'' <small>(Gould, 1843)</small> \u2013 ranging across Northern Australia from Kimberley Divide (Western Australia) to northern and western Queensland (including Cape York Peninsula) and southward to the northern Great Sandy and Tanami Deserts, Central Australian ranges, northern Simpson Desert and central Thomson drainage.\n* ''S. b. ochrogaster'' <small>(Schodde & Mason, 1999)</small> \u2013 western and central Western Australia (south from the Pilbara).\n* ''S. b. occidentalis'' <small>(Bonaparte, 1850)</small> \u2013 southwest Western Australia (south from lower Murchison Range and Kalgoorlie region), eastward around southern rim of Nullarbor Plain to South Australia (southward from central Flinders Ranges, lower Frome Basin and Murray Mallee).\n* ''S. b. brevirostris'' <small>(Gould, 1838)</small> \u2013 Eastern Australia from central and eastern Queensland (Burdekin drainage), southward to Victoria and southeast South Australia.\n\n== Description ==\nThe weebill is [[Australia]]'s smallest bird at approximately {{convert|8|to|9|cm|in|abbr=on}} long and weighing an average of 6 grams (adult bird).<ref name=HANZAB>{{Cite book|title=Handbook of Australian, New Zealand and Antarctic Birds, Volume 6: Pardalotes to Shrike-thrushes.|author=Higgins, P. J.|author2=J. M. Peter|last-author-amp=yes|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2002|isbn=0-19-553244-9|location=Melbourne|pages=}}</ref> Wingspan is approximately {{convert|15|cm|in|abbr=on}}.<ref name=HANZAB/>\n\nWeebills have inconspicuously coloured [[plumage]] ranging from yellowish-grey (front) to olive-brownish-grey (back). The two main feather pigments involved in this variation are yellow ([[phaeomelanin]]) and olive-brown ([[eumelanin]]).<ref name=\"keast1958\" /> There is geographical variation in plumage across the four subspecies.<ref name=HANZAB/>\n\nAdults have pale yellow eyes and a faint cream coloured [[supercilium]]. The throat feathers are grey often with striation and the flight feathers on the wings are pale brown.<ref name=HANZAB/> The tail feathers are brown with a black bar and white spot on the tip of all the [[rectrices]] except the central pairs which are completely dark.<ref name=\":5\" /> Both sexes are [[Monomorphism (biology)|monomorphic]] in plumage colouration.<ref name=HANZAB/>\n\nThe [[Beak|bill]] is short and pale grey,<ref name=\":0\" /> the stubby bill of the weebill assists in distinguishing it from [[Acanthiza|thornbills]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Field guide to the birds of Australia|edition=5th|author=Simpson|author2=Day|last-author-amp=yes|publisher=Penguin Books Australia Ltd.|year=1996|isbn=067086305X|location=Ringwood, VIC, Australia|pages=182}}</ref> The legs and feet of the weebill are grey, like all passerines, their [[Bird feet and legs|toe arrangement]] is [[anisodactyl]] for perching.<ref name=HANZAB/>\n\nJuveniles have a similar plumage to adults but can be identified by a brighter, yellow bill and greyer eye.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nFour subspecies of weebill are currently recognised and exhibit slight variation in feather pigmentation dependent on distribution;<ref name=HANZAB/> In the south and east of Australia, subspecies ''occidentalis'' and ''brevirostris'' are light brown, in the south west subspecies ''occidentalis'' exhibits greyer plumage, while subspecies ''flavescens'' in northern and inland Australia are paler and more yellow.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://mdahlem.net/birds/17/weebill.php|title=Weebill (Smicrornis brevirostris)|website=mdahlem.net|access-date=2019-06-09}}</ref> Additionally, the Northern Australia weebills are smaller than those in the south.\n\nThe voice of the weebill is a loud, clear, musical \"''pee-pee p'wee''\", \"''wee bit''\" or \"''wee willy weetee''\", often heard from a considerable distance.<ref name=HANZAB/>\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\nThe weebill is found in [[woodland]]s and forests across most of mainland [[Australia]], excluding Tasmania.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.feathersandphotos.com.au/forum/showwiki.php?title=Australian+Bird+Guide:Weebill+Smicrornis+brevirostris|title=Weebill (Smicrornis brevirostris) - Feathers and Photos - Australia's birding and bird photography forum|website=www.feathersandphotos.com.au|access-date=2019-06-09}}</ref>  All four subspecies of weebills are sedentary in their range,<ref name=HANZAB/> and numbers are regular throughout the year.\n\nThey are most commonly found in the canopies of dry open [[eucalyptus]] forests, woodlands and [[Mallee Woodlands and Shrublands|mallee]],<ref name=\":2\" /> occasionally coming down to the [[Stratification (vegetation)|mid stratum]] to feed primarily on small insects and their larvae. They display a preference for foraging in the canopy foliage of healthy eucalyptus trees, where they are more likely to retrieve insects.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fleming|first=P. A.|last2=Hardy|first2=G. E. StJ|last3=Craig|first3=M. D.|last4=Valentine|first4=L. E.|last5=Moore|first5=T. L.|date=2013|title=Do woodland birds prefer to forage in healthy Eucalyptus wandoo trees?|journal=Australian Journal of Zoology|volume=61|issue=3|pages=187\u2013195|doi=10.1071/ZO13045|issn=0004-959X|url=https://research-repository.uwa.edu.au/en/publications/do-woodland-birds-prefer-to-forage-in-healthy-eucalyptus-wandoo-trees(78751a98-2a0d-4943-9adb-b03b92a16abf).html}}</ref> The weebill is widespread in all climates,<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=The directory of Australian birds: passerines|author=Schodde, R.|author2=Mason, I. J.|last-author-amp=yes|publisher=CSIRO Publishing|year=1999|isbn=9780643064560|location=Collingwood, VIC, Australia|pages=}}</ref> localised to watercourses in arid zones. They are somewhat gregarious with other small insectivorous passerines such as [[Acanthiza|thornbills]], [[silvereye]]s and [[pardalote]]s.\n\n== Ecology ==\n=== Diet ===\nThe diet consists mostly of [[insect]]s, [[larva]]e and occasionally seeds.<ref name=HANZAB/> [[Arthropod]] prey items include spiders ([[Spider|Araneae]]), beetles ([[Beetle|Coleoptera]], including [[Curculionidae|Curculionids]]) and flies ([[Fly|Diptera]]).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Handbook of the Birds of the World Alive; Volume 12: Picathartes to Tits and Chickadees|author=del Hoyo, J.|author2=Elliott, A.|author3=Sargatal, J.|author4=Christie, D.A.|author5=de Juana, E.|last-author-amp=yes|publisher=Lynx Edicions|year=2007|isbn=9788496553422|location=Barcelona|pages=}}</ref> Weebills forage busily in pairs or small parties of up to 6 to 8 feeding mainly in trees, often hovering, they are active and noisy and cling to twigs while gleaning insects from the outer foliage of the canopy and mid-canopy.\n\nWeebills assist in maintaining the health of trees as they [[Gleaning (birds)|glean]] scale insects and eat a range of other insects including [[Psyllidae|psyllids]] and their protective covers [[Lerp (biology)|(lerps)]].<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n=== Reproduction ===\n[[File:Weebill (Smicrornis brevirostris).jpg|thumb|right|Subspecies ''flavescens'', Northern Territory]]\nThe dome-shaped [[Bird nest|pendant nests]] of weebills are made from fine, pliable materials such as grasses and plant fibers suspended from a branch<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|title=The Wrens and Warblers of Australia: The National Photographic Index of Australian Wildlife|last=Serventy|first=Vincent|publisher=Angus & Robertson|year=1982|isbn=020714480X|location=Australia|pages=}}</ref> concealed in dense foliage of the tree canopy. Weebills are known to utilize cobwebs, insect cocoons and animal hair to bind, strengthen and further conceal the nest.\n\nBreeding season of weebills depends on geographic latitude and climatic conditions,<ref name=\":1\" /> they can breed almost any time of the year but most commonly from July to May. Courtship displays have been observed in weebills, where males ruffle cheek and head feathers with outstretched wings to the female. It is thought that male and female weebills display to each other at the nest-site with tail-fanning, slight bowing and wing quivering.<ref name=HANZAB/>\n\nThe female usually lays two to four brown-speckled cream-colored [[Bird egg|eggs]]<ref name=HANZAB/> which are tapered-oval in shape. Only the female [[Egg incubation|incubates]] the eggs which hatch after 10\u201312 days, but both parents care for the chicks.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.birdsinbackyards.net/species/Smicrornis-brevirostris|title=Weebill {{!}} BIRDS in BACKYARDS|website=www.birdsinbackyards.net|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref>\n\nWeebill eggs in the nest are occasionally vulnerable to small [[brood parasite]]s such as the [[Horsfield's bronze cuckoo]], where the female cuckoo removes the weebill eggs and lays one or two eggs in the host nest for the weebill to raise.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.birdlife.org.au/bird-profile/horsfields-bronze-cuckoo|title=Horsfield's Bronze-Cuckoo {{!}} BirdLife Australia|last=http://www.carterdigital.com.au|first=Carter Digital-|website=www.birdlife.org.au|language=en|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref>\n\n== Threats and conservation ==\nWidespread and common in its habitat throughout its [[range (biology)|range]] on mainland Australia, the weebill is evaluated as Least Concern on the [[IUCN Red List]] of Threatened Species.<ref>[[BirdLife International]] ''(2012).'' \"''Smicrornis brevirostris''\"''. [[IUCN Red List|IUCN Red List of Threatened Species.]] Version 2013.2.'' [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]]''. Retrieved 26 November 2013''</ref> However, like many woodland birds throughout Australia, local declines have been noted, these being consequent of [[Habitat destruction|habitat loss]] and fragmentation caused by deforestation of ''[[Eucalyptus]]'' woodlands<ref>http://www.birdlife.org.au/documents/WL-woodland_birdsWS.pdf</ref> and other [[Human impact on the environment|anthropogenic changes]] to the characteristics of land.\n\nHuman-caused disturbances include introduced flora and fauna species, and altered fire regimes that can result in changes to ecosystem-level processes, modify habitat structure and consequently affect fauna assemblages.<ref>{{Cite thesis|title=The impacts of human-mediated disturbances on birds and reptiles in tropical savannas|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/version/47062090|date=2009|degree=Thesis|first=Leonie|last=Valentine|publisher=|doi=}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}<!-- Emu100:324 -->\n* Del Hoyo, J.; Elliot, A. & Christie D. (editors). (2006). Handbook of the Birds of the World. Volume 12: Picathartes to Tits and Chickadees. Lynx Edicions. {{ISBN|978-84-96553-42-2}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Smicrornis brevirostris|''Smicrornis brevirostris''}}\n*{{Wikispecies-inline|Smicrornis brevirostris|''Smicrornis brevirostris''}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1300169}}\n\n[[Category:Acanthizidae]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1838]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by John Gould]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| name              = Weebill\n| image             = Weebill Smicrornis brevirostris) 12 September 2015 Cropped.jpg\n| image_caption     = Nominate subspecies, Victoria\n| status            = LC\n| status_system     = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref        = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704662/0 |title=''Smicrornis brevirostris'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus             = Smicrornis\n| parent_authority  = [[John Gould|Gould]], 1843\n| species           = brevirostris\n| authority         = ([[John Gould (ornithologist)|Gould]], 1838)\n| range_map         = Weebill_distribution.png\n| range_map_caption = Approximate range in Australia\n{{Leftlegend|#FF0000|Year-round range|outline=gray}}\n}}\n\nThe '''weebill''' (''Smicrornis brevirostris'') is a species of bird in the family [[Acanthizidae]], it is an [[Insectivore|insectivorous]] [[passerine]] that is found throughout mainland [[Australia]]. At {{convert|8|to|9|cm|in|abbr=on}} long, it is Australia's smallest bird. It was originally described by [[John Gould]] in 1838, and four subspecies are recognised. The weebill's plumage is nondescript, with olive-grey upperparts and paler, more yellowish underparts. It grades from more brownish plumage in the southern regions of Australia to more yellow in tropical areas.\n\n== Taxonomy ==\nThe weebill was described by John Gould in 1838 as ''Psilopus brevirostris''. The species epithet is derived from the [[Latin]] words ''brevis'' 'short' and ''rostrum'' 'beak'.<ref name=fraser13>{{cite book|last1=Gray|first1=Jeannie|last2=Fraser|first2=Ian|title=Australian Bird Names: A Complete Guide|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=W1TCqHVWQp0C&pg=PT184|year=2013|publisher=CSIRO Publishing|location=Collingwood, Victoria | isbn=978-0-643-10471-6|page=184}}</ref>\n\nIn 1843, Gould erected the genus ''Smicrornis'' for his new species ''Smicrornis flavescens'', collected from Port Essington, noting it as distinct from ''[[Gerygone]]'' (which had replaced ''Psilopus as a ''name'').<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gould |first1=John |title=Proceedings of meeting of Zoological Society of London, Oct. 11, 1842 |journal=Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London |date=1842 |volume=10 |pages=131\u2013140 [133\u2013134] |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/30679895}}</ref>'' The generic name ''Smicrornis'' derives from the Greek ''smicros'' 'small' and ''ornis'' 'bird'.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling|title=Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird-names|last=Jobling|first=James A.|accessdate = 2020-04-17}}</ref> It is the [[Monotypic taxon|only member]] of genus ''Smicrornis''; [[gene flow]] is strong and local variation follows [[Bergmann's rule|Bergmann's]] and [[Gloger's rule|Gloger's]] rules.<ref name=\"keast1958\">{{cite journal |last1=Keast |first1=Allan |title=Geographic variation in the Weebill, Smicrornis brevirostris (Gould) (Passeres: Muscicapidae, malurinae) a sedentary species with a continuous range |journal=Australian Journal of Zoology |date=1958 |volume=6 |issue=2 |pages=152\u2013161 |doi=10.1071/ZO9580152}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://bie.ala.org.au/species/urn:lsid:biodiversity.org.au:afd.taxon:e2e2e858-5403-4981-8baf-b5202275fa7a|title=Smicrornis brevirostris : Weebill|last=Australia|first=Atlas of Living|website=bie.ala.org.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref>\n\nGould initially called it the short-billed smicrornis, but it did not gain acceptance. Other names include tree-tit, short billed tree-tit, scrub-tit, or short-billed scrub-tit. Weebill was adopted as the name in the 1926 RAOU checklist.<ref name=fraser13/>\n\n=== Subspecies ===\nFour [[subspecies]] are currently recognised in addition to the nominate subspecies:<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n* S. ''b''. ''flavescens'' <small>(Gould, 1843)</small> \u2013 ranging across Northern Australia from Kimberley Divide (Western Australia) to northern and western Queensland (including Cape York Peninsula) and southward to the northern Great Sandy and Tanami Deserts, Central Australian ranges, northern Simpson Desert and central Thomson drainage.\n* ''S. b. ochrogaster'' <small>(Schodde & Mason, 1999)</small> \u2013 western and central Western Australia (south from the Pilbara).\n* ''S. b. occidentalis'' <small>(Bonaparte, 1850)</small> \u2013 southwest Western Australia (south from lower Murchison Range and Kalgoorlie region), eastward around southern rim of Nullarbor Plain to South Australia (southward from central Flinders Ranges, lower Frome Basin and Murray Mallee).\n* ''S. b. brevirostris'' <small>(Gould, 1838)</small> \u2013 Eastern Australia from central and eastern Queensland (Burdekin drainage), southward to Victoria and southeast South Australia.\n\n== Description ==\nThe weebill is [[Australia]]'s smallest bird at approximately {{convert|8|to|9|cm|in|abbr=on}} long and weighing an average of 6 grams (adult bird).<ref name=HANZAB>{{Cite book|title=Handbook of Australian, New Zealand and Antarctic Birds, Volume 6: Pardalotes to Shrike-thrushes.|author=Higgins, P. J.|author2=J. M. Peter|last-author-amp=yes|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2002|isbn=0-19-553244-9|location=Melbourne|pages=}}</ref> Wingspan is approximately {{convert|15|cm|in|abbr=on}}.<ref name=HANZAB/>\n\nWeebills have inconspicuously coloured [[plumage]] ranging from yellowish-grey (front) to olive-brownish-grey (back). The two main feather pigments involved in this variation are yellow ([[phaeomelanin]]) and olive-brown ([[eumelanin]]).<ref name=\"keast1958\" /> There is geographical variation in plumage across the four subspecies.<ref name=HANZAB/>\n\nAdults have pale yellow eyes and a faint cream coloured [[supercilium]]. The throat feathers are grey often with striation and the flight feathers on the wings are pale brown.<ref name=HANZAB/> The tail feathers are brown with a black bar and white spot on the tip of all the [[rectrices]] except the central pairs which are completely dark.<ref name=\":5\" /> Both sexes are [[Monomorphism (biology)|monomorphic]] in plumage colouration.<ref name=HANZAB/>\n\nThe [[Beak|bill]] is short and pale grey,<ref name=\":0\" /> the stubby bill of the weebill assists in distinguishing it from [[Acanthiza|thornbills]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Field guide to the birds of Australia|edition=5th|author=Simpson|author2=Day|last-author-amp=yes|publisher=Penguin Books Australia Ltd.|year=1996|isbn=067086305X|location=Ringwood, VIC, Australia|pages=182}}</ref> The legs and feet of the weebill are grey, like all passerines, their [[Bird feet and legs|toe arrangement]] is [[anisodactyl]] for perching.<ref name=HANZAB/>\n\nJuveniles have a similar plumage to adults but can be identified by a brighter, yellow bill and greyer eye.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nFour subspecies of weebill are currently recognised and exhibit slight variation in feather pigmentation dependent on distribution;<ref name=HANZAB/> In the south and east of Australia, subspecies ''occidentalis'' and ''brevirostris'' are light brown, in the south west subspecies ''occidentalis'' exhibits greyer plumage, while subspecies ''flavescens'' in northern and inland Australia are paler and more yellow.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://mdahlem.net/birds/17/weebill.php|title=Weebill (Smicrornis brevirostris)|website=mdahlem.net|access-date=2019-06-09}}</ref> Additionally, the Northern Australia weebills are smaller than those in the south.\n\nThe voice of the weebill is a loud, clear, musical \"''pee-pee p'wee''\", \"''wee bit''\" or \"''wee willy weetee''\", often heard from a considerable distance.<ref name=HANZAB/>\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\nThe weebill is found in [[woodland]]s and forests across most of mainland [[Australia]], excluding Tasmania.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.feathersandphotos.com.au/forum/showwiki.php?title=Australian+Bird+Guide:Weebill+Smicrornis+brevirostris|title=Weebill (Smicrornis brevirostris) - Feathers and Photos - Australia's birding and bird photography forum|website=www.feathersandphotos.com.au|access-date=2019-06-09}}</ref>  All four subspecies of weebills are sedentary in their range,<ref name=HANZAB/> and numbers are regular throughout the year.\n\nThey are most commonly found in the canopies of dry open [[eucalyptus]] forests, woodlands and [[Mallee Woodlands and Shrublands|mallee]],<ref name=\":2\" /> occasionally coming down to the [[Stratification (vegetation)|mid stratum]] to feed primarily on small insects and their larvae. They display a preference for foraging in the canopy foliage of healthy eucalyptus trees, where they are more likely to retrieve insects.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fleming|first=P. A.|last2=Hardy|first2=G. E. StJ|last3=Craig|first3=M. D.|last4=Valentine|first4=L. E.|last5=Moore|first5=T. L.|date=2013|title=Do woodland birds prefer to forage in healthy Eucalyptus wandoo trees?|journal=Australian Journal of Zoology|volume=61|issue=3|pages=187\u2013195|doi=10.1071/ZO13045|issn=0004-959X|url=https://research-repository.uwa.edu.au/en/publications/do-woodland-birds-prefer-to-forage-in-healthy-eucalyptus-wandoo-trees(78751a98-2a0d-4943-9adb-b03b92a16abf).html}}</ref> The weebill is widespread in all climates,<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=The directory of Australian birds: passerines|author=Schodde, R.|author2=Mason, I. J.|last-author-amp=yes|publisher=CSIRO Publishing|year=1999|isbn=9780643064560|location=Collingwood, VIC, Australia|pages=}}</ref> localised to watercourses in arid zones. They are somewhat gregarious with other small insectivorous passerines such as [[Acanthiza|thornbills]], [[silvereye]]s and [[pardalote]]s.\n\n== Ecology ==\n=== Diet ===\nThe diet consists mostly of [[insect]]s, [[larva]]e and occasionally seeds.<ref name=HANZAB/> [[Arthropod]] prey items include spiders ([[Spider|Araneae]]), beetles ([[Beetle|Coleoptera]], including [[Curculionidae|Curculionids]]) and flies ([[Fly|Diptera]]).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Handbook of the Birds of the World Alive; Volume 12: Picathartes to Tits and Chickadees|author=del Hoyo, J.|author2=Elliott, A.|author3=Sargatal, J.|author4=Christie, D.A.|author5=de Juana, E.|last-author-amp=yes|publisher=Lynx Edicions|year=2007|isbn=9788496553422|location=Barcelona|pages=}}</ref> Weebills forage busily in pairs or small parties of up to 6 to 8 feeding mainly in trees, often hovering, they are active and noisy and cling to twigs while gleaning insects from the outer foliage of the canopy and mid-canopy.\n\nWeebills assist in maintaining the health of trees as they [[Gleaning (birds)|glean]] scale insects and eat a range of other insects including [[Psyllidae|psyllids]] and their protective covers [[Lerp (biology)|(lerps)]].<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n=== Reproduction ===\n[[File:Weebill (Smicrornis brevirostris).jpg|thumb|right|Subspecies ''flavescens'', Northern Territory]]\nThe dome-shaped [[Bird nest|pendant nests]] of weebills are made from fine, pliable materials such as grasses and plant fibers suspended from a branch<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|title=The Wrens and Warblers of Australia: The National Photographic Index of Australian Wildlife|last=Serventy|first=Vincent|publisher=Angus & Robertson|year=1982|isbn=020714480X|location=Australia|pages=}}</ref> concealed in dense foliage of the tree canopy. Weebills are known to utilize cobwebs, insect cocoons and animal hair to bind, strengthen and further conceal the nest.\n\nBreeding season of weebills depends on geographic latitude and climatic conditions,<ref name=\":1\" /> they can breed almost any time of the year but most commonly from July to May. Courtship displays have been observed in weebills, where males ruffle cheek and head feathers with outstretched wings to the female. It is thought that male and female weebills display to each other at the nest-site with tail-fanning, slight bowing and wing quivering.<ref name=HANZAB/>\n\nThe female usually lays two to four brown-speckled cream-colored [[Bird egg|eggs]]<ref name=HANZAB/> which are tapered-oval in shape. Only the female [[Egg incubation|incubates]] the eggs which hatch after 10\u201312 days, but both parents care for the chicks.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.birdsinbackyards.net/species/Smicrornis-brevirostris|title=Weebill {{!}} BIRDS in BACKYARDS|website=www.birdsinbackyards.net|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref>\n\nWeebill eggs in the nest are occasionally vulnerable to small [[brood parasite]]s such as the [[Horsfield's bronze cuckoo]], where the female cuckoo removes the weebill eggs and lays one or two eggs in the host nest for the weebill to raise.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.birdlife.org.au/bird-profile/horsfields-bronze-cuckoo|title=Horsfield's Bronze-Cuckoo {{!}} BirdLife Australia|last=http://www.carterdigital.com.au|first=Carter Digital-|website=www.birdlife.org.au|language=en|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref>\n\n== Threats and conservation ==\nWidespread and common in its habitat throughout its [[range (biology)|range]] on mainland Australia, the weebill is evaluated as Least Concern on the [[IUCN Red List]] of Threatened Species.<ref>[[BirdLife International]] ''(2012).'' \"''Smicrornis brevirostris''\"''. [[IUCN Red List|IUCN Red List of Threatened Species.]] Version 2013.2.'' [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]]''. Retrieved 26 November 2013''</ref> However, like many woodland birds throughout Australia, local declines have been noted, these being consequent of [[Habitat destruction|habitat loss]] and fragmentation caused by deforestation of ''[[Eucalyptus]]'' woodlands<ref>http://www.birdlife.org.au/documents/WL-woodland_birdsWS.pdf</ref> and other [[Human impact on the environment|anthropogenic changes]] to the characteristics of land.\n\nHuman-caused disturbances include introduced flora and fauna species, and altered fire regimes that can result in changes to ecosystem-level processes, modify habitat structure and consequently affect fauna assemblages.<ref>{{Cite thesis|title=The impacts of human-mediated disturbances on birds and reptiles in tropical savannas|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/version/47062090|date=2009|degree=Thesis|first=Leonie|last=Valentine|publisher=|doi=}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}<!-- Emu100:324 -->\n* Del Hoyo, J.; Elliot, A. & Christie D. (editors). (2006). Handbook of the Birds of the World. Volume 12: Picathartes to Tits and Chickadees. Lynx Edicions. {{ISBN|978-84-96553-42-2}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Smicrornis brevirostris|''Smicrornis brevirostris''}}\n*{{Wikispecies-inline|Smicrornis brevirostris|''Smicrornis brevirostris''}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1300169}}\n\n[[Category:Acanthizidae]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1838]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by John Gould]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTaxonomy:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weebill"}
{"title_page": "John Rudolph Sutermeister", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=August 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name         = John Rudolph Sutermeister\n| image        = \n| imagesize    = \n| caption      = \n| birth_name    = \n| pseudonym     = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|mf=yes|1803|3|16}}\n| birth_place   = [[Cura\u00e7ao]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|mf=yes|1826|1|16|1803|3|16}}\n| death_place   = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| occupation   = Lawyer, poet\n| nationality  = American\n| signature    = \n| notableworks = \n| spouse       = \n| children     = \n| influenced   = \n}}\n\n'''John Rudolph Sutermeister''' (March 16, 1803 \u2013 January 16, 1826)<ref name=\"curacao\">{{cite web |url=http://caribischegenealogie.org/genealogieen-n-z/sutermeister/ |title=Caribische Genealogie - Familiegeschiedenissen van overzee |accessdate=2015-08-08 }}</ref> was an American [[jurist]] and [[poet]].\n\n== Life ==\n\nSutermeister was baptized at a Lutheran church in [[Cura\u00e7ao]], his birthplace, 17 April 1803.<ref name=\"curacao\"/> Upon arrival in [[Rhinebeck (town), New York|Rhinebeck]] around 1812 he studied at the [[Lutheran church]]. In 1817 he was sent to boarding school in [[Cooperstown, New York]]. After studying alternately at the Rhinebeck Hartwick Academy, he studied [[law]] at Rhinebeck. In 1824 he began a tour through the western part of the state of New York to find a suitable location to establish itself as a lawyer. He settled in the same year in [[Syracuse, New York]]. However, the legal profession did not suit him and he then worked briefly as editor of the ''[[Syracuse Gazette]]''. In July 1825 he left Syracuse to move to [[New York City]] where his friends had found a suitable and lucrative position for him. However, this was short-lived because six months later he died.<ref name=\"curacao\"/>\n\nJohn made himself a poet deserving in his short life.<ref>[[Samuel Kettell]]. ''Specimens of American Poetry, with Biographical and Critical Notices'', vol. III, pp. 72-75, New York. 1967.</ref>\n\n== Work ==\n\nIn 1824 Sutermeister wrote an ''Ode to [[Linn\u00e6us]],<ref>[http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.32044107269888;view=1up;seq=18 ''Celebration at Flushing, of the Birth-Day of Linnaeus.'' New-York Branch of the Linnaean Society of Paris, 1824, p. 14] [http://dp.la/item/e0b5b22b7b13356ea3010bed351a2b61 description] at the [[Digital Public Library of America]]</ref> \nwhich was also published in the ''[[American Farmer]]''<ref>[https://books.google.ch/books?id=J25_M7apXB0C&pg=PA161&lpg=PA161&dq=%22Ode+to+Linnaeus%22&source=bl&ots=mMxueaWvJb&sig=YhO7TRX42FUsKzDyOwWFdDHyQPw&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0CDMQ6AEwBGoVChMI9ZLuqb_zxgIVg5MsCh1kqAZf#v=onepage&q=%22Ode%20to%20Linnaeus%22&f=false no. 21, vol. 6, Baltimore, 13 August 1824, p. 161]</ref>\n\nThe same year, he wrote the poem ''To a Humming Bird'',<ref>[http://external.oneonta.edu/cooper/articles/other/2010other-harthorn.html Excerpt]</ref> which was published in [[John Keese]]'s [https://books.google.ch/books?id=cg0TAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA124&dq=%22To+A+Humming+Bird%22+Sutermeister&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0CCoQ6AEwAGoVChMI1dGH8sTzxgIVywUsCh2gigp5#v=onepage&q=%22To%20A%20Humming%20Bird%22%20Sutermeister&f=false ''The Poets of America'']<ref>volume 1, S. Colman, 1840, p. 124-125</ref> as well as in [[Anthony Benezet Cleveland]]'s ''Studies in Poetry and Prose''<ref>Selections Principally from American Writers, and Designed for the Highest Class in Schools. W. and J. Neal, 1832, p. 360.</ref>\n\nA year later, he wrote ''The Garden''; his poems were published as ''Minor Poems'' (including ''A Contrasted Picture'',<ref>{{IA|specimensameric01kettgoog}}, p. 72-73.</ref> ''The Lament'' (or ''A Lament''),<ref>[http://www.gutenberg.org/files/19383/19383-h/19383-h.htm Digitalized by Gutenberg.org, including biographical background], p. 73-74.</ref> ''Faded Hours''<ref>{{IA|specimensameric01kettgoog}}, p. 74-75. ([[Rufus Wilmot Griswold]]: [https://books.google.ch/books?id=_-QYAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA545&dq=%22faded+hours%22+Sutermeister&hl=de&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22faded%20hours%22%20Sutermeister&f=false ''The Poets and Poetry of America: To the Middle of the Nineteenth Century.'' A. Hart, 1852, p. 545.]</ref> (The Careless Lover's Adieu'') and in the ''[[Syracuse Gazette]]''.\n\n=== Poems (selection) ===\n\n* ''Ode to [[Author:Carl Linnaeus|Linn\u00e6us]].'' [http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.32044107269888;view=1up;seq=18 ''Celebration at Flushing, of the Birth-Day of Linnaeus.'' New-York Branch of the Linnaean Society of Paris, 1824, p. 14] ([http://dp.la/item/e0b5b22b7b13356ea3010bed351a2b61 description] at the [[:w:Digital Public Library of America|Digital Public Library of America]])\n::Published also in: ''[[American Farmer]]'', no. 21, vol. 6, Baltimore, 13 August 1824, p. 161 ([https://books.google.ch/books?id=J25_M7apXB0C&pg=PA161&lpg=PA161&dq=%22Ode+to+Linnaeus%22&source=bl&ots=mMxueaWvJb&sig=YhO7TRX42FUsKzDyOwWFdDHyQPw&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0CDMQ6AEwBGoVChMI9ZLuqb_zxgIVg5MsCh1kqAZf#v=onepage&q=%22Ode%20to%20Linnaeus%22&f=false online])\n* ''To a Humming Bird.'' (originally appeared in 1824) ([http://external.oneonta.edu/cooper/articles/other/2010other-harthorn.html Excerpt])\n::Published in: [[Author:John Keese|John Keese]]: [https://books.google.ch/books?id=cg0TAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA124&dq=%22To+A+Humming+Bird%22+Sutermeister&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0CCoQ6AEwAGoVChMI1dGH8sTzxgIVywUsCh2gigp5#v=onepage&q=%22To%20A%20Humming%20Bird%22%20Sutermeister&f=false ''The Poets of America'', volume 1, S. Colman, 1840], p. 124-125.\n::And in: [[Author:A. B. Cleveland|A. B. Cleveland]]: [https://books.google.ch/books?id=49sQAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA360&dq=%22To+A+Humming+Bird%22+Sutermeister&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAWoVChMI1dGH8sTzxgIVywUsCh2gigp5#v=onepage&q=Sutermeister&f=false ''Studies in Poetry and Prose: Consisting of Selections Principally from American Writers, and Designed for the Highest Class in Schools.'' W. and J. Neal, 1832], p. 360.\n* ''The Garden.'' (1825)\n* ''Minor Poems.''\n* ''A Contrasted Picture.'' ({{IA|specimensameric01kettgoog}}, p.&nbsp;72-73.)\n* ''The Lament'' or ''A Lament''. ([http://www.gutenberg.org/files/19383/19383-h/19383-h.htm Digitalized by Gutenberg.org, including biographical background]) ({{IA|specimensameric01kettgoog}}, p.&nbsp;73-74.)\n* ''Faded Hours.'' ({{IA|specimensameric01kettgoog}}, p.&nbsp;74-75.) ([[Author:Rufus Wilmot Griswold|Rufus Wilmot Griswold]]: [https://books.google.ch/books?id=_-QYAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA545&dq=%22faded+hours%22+Sutermeister&hl=de&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22faded%20hours%22%20Sutermeister&f=false ''The Poets and Poetry of America: To the Middle of the Nineteenth Century.'' A. Hart, 1852, p. 545.])\n* ''[https://books.google.ch/books?id=13QtAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA95&lpg=PA95&dq=%22J.+R.+Sutermeister%22&source=bl&ots=5onB7rD5T0&sig=1gyHFJkfWZev87gMfzURc6IcrLk&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0CB0Q6AEwADgKahUKEwiCho27xvPGAhXI6CwKHYgIATg#v=onepage&q=%22J.%20R.%20Sutermeister%22&f=false The Careless Lover's Adieu]''\n\n== References ==\n\n<references/>\n\n== Bibliography and Weblinks ==\n\n{{wikisource author}}\n\n* [[Samuel Kettell]]: ''Specimens of American poetry: with critical and biographical notices, in three volumes.'' Boston: S.G. Goodrich, 1829, p.&nbsp;71-75. {{IA|specimensameric01kettgoog}}\n* [http://caribischegenealogie.org/genealogieen-n-z/sutermeister/ Short biography, caribbean genealogy]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sutermeister, John Rudolph}}\n[[Category:1803 births]]\n[[Category:1826 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century American poets]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Lutheran poets]]\n[[Category:American Lutherans]]\n[[Category:Cura\u00e7ao emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Cura\u00e7ao jurists]]\n[[Category:Cura\u00e7ao poets]]\n[[Category:19th-century American male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=August 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name         = John Rudolph Sutermeister\n| image        = \n| imagesize    = \n| caption      = \n| birth_name    = \n| pseudonym     = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|mf=yes|1803|3|16}}\n| birth_place   = [[Cura\u00e7ao]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|mf=yes|1826|1|16|1803|3|16}}\n| death_place   = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| occupation   = Lawyer, poet\n| nationality  = American\n| signature    = \n| notableworks = \n| spouse       = \n| children     = \n| influenced   = \n}}\n\n'''John Rudolph Sutermeister''' ([[Cura\u00e7ao]], March 16, 1803&nbsp;\u2013 [[New York City]], January 16, 1826),<ref name=\"curacao\">{{cite web |url=http://caribischegenealogie.org/genealogieen-n-z/sutermeister/ |title=Caribische Genealogie - Familiegeschiedenissen van overzee |accessdate=2015-08-08 }}</ref> was an American [[jurist]] and [[poet]].\n\n== Life ==\n\nSutermeister was baptized at a Lutheran church in [[Cura\u00e7ao]], his birthplace, 17 April 1803.<ref name=\"curacao\"/> Upon arrival in [[Rhinebeck (town), New York|Rhinebeck]] around 1812 he studied at the [[Lutheran church]]. In 1817 he was sent to boarding school in [[Cooperstown, New York]]. After studying alternately at the Rhinebeck Hartwick Academy, he studied [[law]] at Rhinebeck. In 1824 he began a tour through the western part of the state of New York to find a suitable location to establish itself as a lawyer. He settled in the same year in [[Syracuse, New York]]. However, the legal profession did not suit him and he then worked briefly as editor of the ''[[Syracuse Gazette]]''. In July 1825 he left Syracuse to move to [[New York City]] where his friends had found a suitable and lucrative position for him. However, this was short-lived because six months later he died.<ref name=\"curacao\"/>\n\nJohn made himself a poet deserving in his short life.<ref>[[Samuel Kettell]]. ''Specimens of American Poetry, with Biographical and Critical Notices'', vol. III, pp. 72-75, New York. 1967.</ref>\n\n== Work ==\n\nIn 1824 Sutermeister wrote an ''Ode to [[Linn\u00e6us]],<ref>[http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.32044107269888;view=1up;seq=18 ''Celebration at Flushing, of the Birth-Day of Linnaeus.'' New-York Branch of the Linnaean Society of Paris, 1824, p. 14] [http://dp.la/item/e0b5b22b7b13356ea3010bed351a2b61 description] at the [[Digital Public Library of America]]</ref> \nwhich was also published in the ''[[American Farmer]]''<ref>[https://books.google.ch/books?id=J25_M7apXB0C&pg=PA161&lpg=PA161&dq=%22Ode+to+Linnaeus%22&source=bl&ots=mMxueaWvJb&sig=YhO7TRX42FUsKzDyOwWFdDHyQPw&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0CDMQ6AEwBGoVChMI9ZLuqb_zxgIVg5MsCh1kqAZf#v=onepage&q=%22Ode%20to%20Linnaeus%22&f=false no. 21, vol. 6, Baltimore, 13 August 1824, p. 161]</ref>\n\nThe same year, he wrote the poem ''To a Humming Bird'',<ref>[http://external.oneonta.edu/cooper/articles/other/2010other-harthorn.html Excerpt]</ref> which was published in [[John Keese]]'s [https://books.google.ch/books?id=cg0TAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA124&dq=%22To+A+Humming+Bird%22+Sutermeister&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0CCoQ6AEwAGoVChMI1dGH8sTzxgIVywUsCh2gigp5#v=onepage&q=%22To%20A%20Humming%20Bird%22%20Sutermeister&f=false ''The Poets of America'']<ref>volume 1, S. Colman, 1840, p. 124-125</ref> as well as in [[Anthony Benezet Cleveland]]'s ''Studies in Poetry and Prose''<ref>Selections Principally from American Writers, and Designed for the Highest Class in Schools. W. and J. Neal, 1832, p. 360.</ref>\n\nA year later, he wrote ''The Garden''; his poems were published as ''Minor Poems'' (including ''A Contrasted Picture'',<ref>{{IA|specimensameric01kettgoog}}, p. 72-73.</ref> ''The Lament'' (or ''A Lament''),<ref>[http://www.gutenberg.org/files/19383/19383-h/19383-h.htm Digitalized by Gutenberg.org, including biographical background], p. 73-74.</ref> ''Faded Hours''<ref>{{IA|specimensameric01kettgoog}}, p. 74-75. ([[Rufus Wilmot Griswold]]: [https://books.google.ch/books?id=_-QYAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA545&dq=%22faded+hours%22+Sutermeister&hl=de&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22faded%20hours%22%20Sutermeister&f=false ''The Poets and Poetry of America: To the Middle of the Nineteenth Century.'' A. Hart, 1852, p. 545.]</ref> (The Careless Lover's Adieu'') and in the ''[[Syracuse Gazette]]''.\n\n=== Poems (selection) ===\n\n* ''Ode to [[Author:Carl Linnaeus|Linn\u00e6us]].'' [http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.32044107269888;view=1up;seq=18 ''Celebration at Flushing, of the Birth-Day of Linnaeus.'' New-York Branch of the Linnaean Society of Paris, 1824, p. 14] ([http://dp.la/item/e0b5b22b7b13356ea3010bed351a2b61 description] at the [[:w:Digital Public Library of America|Digital Public Library of America]])\n::Published also in: ''[[American Farmer]]'', no. 21, vol. 6, Baltimore, 13 August 1824, p. 161 ([https://books.google.ch/books?id=J25_M7apXB0C&pg=PA161&lpg=PA161&dq=%22Ode+to+Linnaeus%22&source=bl&ots=mMxueaWvJb&sig=YhO7TRX42FUsKzDyOwWFdDHyQPw&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0CDMQ6AEwBGoVChMI9ZLuqb_zxgIVg5MsCh1kqAZf#v=onepage&q=%22Ode%20to%20Linnaeus%22&f=false online])\n* ''To a Humming Bird.'' (originally appeared in 1824) ([http://external.oneonta.edu/cooper/articles/other/2010other-harthorn.html Excerpt])\n::Published in: [[Author:John Keese|John Keese]]: [https://books.google.ch/books?id=cg0TAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA124&dq=%22To+A+Humming+Bird%22+Sutermeister&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0CCoQ6AEwAGoVChMI1dGH8sTzxgIVywUsCh2gigp5#v=onepage&q=%22To%20A%20Humming%20Bird%22%20Sutermeister&f=false ''The Poets of America'', volume 1, S. Colman, 1840], p. 124-125.\n::And in: [[Author:A. B. Cleveland|A. B. Cleveland]]: [https://books.google.ch/books?id=49sQAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA360&dq=%22To+A+Humming+Bird%22+Sutermeister&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAWoVChMI1dGH8sTzxgIVywUsCh2gigp5#v=onepage&q=Sutermeister&f=false ''Studies in Poetry and Prose: Consisting of Selections Principally from American Writers, and Designed for the Highest Class in Schools.'' W. and J. Neal, 1832], p. 360.\n* ''The Garden.'' (1825)\n* ''Minor Poems.''\n* ''A Contrasted Picture.'' ({{IA|specimensameric01kettgoog}}, p.&nbsp;72-73.)\n* ''The Lament'' or ''A Lament''. ([http://www.gutenberg.org/files/19383/19383-h/19383-h.htm Digitalized by Gutenberg.org, including biographical background]) ({{IA|specimensameric01kettgoog}}, p.&nbsp;73-74.)\n* ''Faded Hours.'' ({{IA|specimensameric01kettgoog}}, p.&nbsp;74-75.) ([[Author:Rufus Wilmot Griswold|Rufus Wilmot Griswold]]: [https://books.google.ch/books?id=_-QYAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA545&dq=%22faded+hours%22+Sutermeister&hl=de&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22faded%20hours%22%20Sutermeister&f=false ''The Poets and Poetry of America: To the Middle of the Nineteenth Century.'' A. Hart, 1852, p. 545.])\n* ''[https://books.google.ch/books?id=13QtAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA95&lpg=PA95&dq=%22J.+R.+Sutermeister%22&source=bl&ots=5onB7rD5T0&sig=1gyHFJkfWZev87gMfzURc6IcrLk&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0CB0Q6AEwADgKahUKEwiCho27xvPGAhXI6CwKHYgIATg#v=onepage&q=%22J.%20R.%20Sutermeister%22&f=false The Careless Lover's Adieu]''\n\n== References ==\n\n<references/>\n\n== Bibliography and Weblinks ==\n\n{{wikisource author}}\n\n* [[Samuel Kettell]]: ''Specimens of American poetry: with critical and biographical notices, in three volumes.'' Boston: S.G. Goodrich, 1829, p.&nbsp;71-75. {{IA|specimensameric01kettgoog}}\n* [http://caribischegenealogie.org/genealogieen-n-z/sutermeister/ Short biography, caribbean genealogy]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sutermeister, John Rudolph}}\n[[Category:1803 births]]\n[[Category:1826 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century American poets]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Lutheran poets]]\n[[Category:American Lutherans]]\n[[Category:Cura\u00e7ao emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Cura\u00e7ao jurists]]\n[[Category:Cura\u00e7ao poets]]\n[[Category:19th-century American male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Stereodice", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed birthplace and death place from parenthetical", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Rudolph_Sutermeister"}
{"title_page": "James B. Weaver House", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP\n| name = James B. Weaver House\n| nrhp_type = nhl\n| image = James B. Weaver house from SW 1.jpg\n| caption = \n| location = 102 Weaver Road<br/>[[Bloomfield, Iowa]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|45|19.2|N|92|24|45.4|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Iowa#USA\n| area = {{convert|1|acre|ha}}\n| built = 1865\n| architect =\n| architecture =\n| designated_nrhp_type = May 15, 1975<ref name=\"nhlsum\">{{cite web|url=http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1539&ResourceType=Building|title=James B. Weaver House|accessdate=2007-10-03|work=National Historic Landmark summary listing|publisher=National Park Service|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606050634/http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1539&ResourceType=Building|archivedate=2011-06-06}}</ref>\n| added = May 15, 1975<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref>\n| refnum = 75000680\n}}\n\nThe '''James B. Weaver House''' is a historic house at 102 Weaver Road ([[United States Route 63]]) in [[Bloomfield, Iowa]].  Built in 1865, it was the home of [[James B. Weaver|James Weaver]] (1833-1912) until 1890. Weaver, a populist and anti-monopolist, was the [[Greenback Party|Greenback]] candidate for president in 1880 and the [[Populist Party (US)|Populist]] candidate in 1892.  The house was declared a [[National Historic Landmark]] in 1975.<ref name=\"nhlsum\"/><ref name=\"nrhpinv2\">{{Cite journal|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination: |url={{NHLS url|id=75000680}} |format=pdf|date=December 1, 1974 |author=George R. Adams |publisher=National Park Service}}. {{NHLS url|id=75000680|title=Accompanying 2 photos, exterior, from 1974.|photos=y}}&nbsp;{{small|(0.99&nbsp;MB)}}</ref>  It is now operated as a bed and breakfast inn.\n\n==Description and history==\nThe Weaver House is located north of downtown Bloomfield, on the east side of Weaver Road just north of its junction with North Street.  It is a two-story L-shaped brick structure, with a gabled roof, five corbelled chimneys, and a single-story ell to the rear.  A two-story porch is set in the crook of the L.  The most prominent feature of the exterior is the windows of its principal elevations, which are set in arched openings framed by dentillated brick hoods.<ref name=\"nrhpinv2\"/>\n\nThe house was built in 1865 for James B. Weaver, an [[Ohio]] native who settled in newly formed Bloomfield in 1847.  Politically active, he helped organize Iowa's [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], and served in the [[Union Army]] in the [[American Civil War]].  A champion of the rural farm electorate, he ran for [[President of the United States]] on the Greenback Party ticket in 1880, and the populist [[People's Party (United States)|People's Party]] in 1892, having helped form the party out of a group of reform-oriented organizations the previous year.<ref name=\"nrhpinv2\"/>\n\nWeaver lived in this house until 1890, when he moved to [[Des Moines, Iowa|Des Moines]].  After passing through several private owners, it was acquired by the Davis County Chautauqua Association, which operated it for a time as a [[historic house museum]].  It was eventually returned to private ownership,<ref name=\"nrhpinv2\"/> and is now operated as a bed and breakfast inn.\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category|James B. Weaver House (Bloomfield, Iowa)}}\n*[[List of National Historic Landmarks in Iowa]]\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Davis County, Iowa]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20171213092142/https://www.theweaverhouseinn.com/ James B. Weaver House Bed and Breakfast]\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places}}\n{{NRHP in Davis County, Iowa}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weaver, James B. House}}\n[[Category:National Historic Landmarks in Iowa]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Davis County, Iowa]]\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in Iowa]]\n[[Category:Houses in Davis County, Iowa]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1865]]\n[[Category:Bloomfield, Iowa]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP\n| name = James B. Weaver House\n| nrhp_type = nhl\n| image = James B. Weaver house from SW 1.jpg\n| caption = \n| location = 102 Weaver Road<br/>[[Bloomfield, Iowa]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|45|19.2|N|92|24|45.4|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Iowa#USA\n| area = {{convert|1|acre|ha}}\n| built = 1865\n| architect =\n| architecture =\n| designated_nrhp_type = May 15, 1975<ref name=\"nhlsum\">{{cite web|url=http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1539&ResourceType=Building|title=James B. Weaver House|accessdate=2007-10-03|work=National Historic Landmark summary listing|publisher=National Park Service|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606050634/http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1539&ResourceType=Building|archivedate=2011-06-06}}</ref>\n| added = May 15, 1975<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref>\n| refnum = 75000680\n}}\n\nThe '''James B. Weaver House''' is a historic house at 102 Weaver Road ([[United States Route 63]]) in [[Bloomfield, Iowa]].  Built in 1865, it was the home of [[James B. Weaver|James Weaver]] (1833-1912) until 1890. Weaver, a populist and anti-monopolist, was the [[Greenback Party|Greenback]] candidate for President in 1880 and the [[Populist Party (US)|Populist]] candidate in 1892.  The house was declared a [[National Historic Landmark]] in 1975.<ref name=\"nhlsum\"/><ref name=\"nrhpinv2\">{{Cite journal|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination: |url={{NHLS url|id=75000680}} |format=pdf|date=December 1, 1974 |author=George R. Adams |publisher=National Park Service}}. {{NHLS url|id=75000680|title=Accompanying 2 photos, exterior, from 1974.|photos=y}}&nbsp;{{small|(0.99&nbsp;MB)}}</ref>  It is now operated as a bed and breakfast inn.\n\n==Description and history==\nThe Weaver House is located north of downtown Bloomfield, on the east side of Weaver Road just north of its junction with North Street.  It is a two-story L-shaped brick structure, with a gabled roof, five corbelled chimneys, and a single-story ell to the rear.  A two-story porch is set in the crook of the L.  The most prominent feature of the exterior is the windows of its principal elevations, which are set in arched openings framed by dentillated brick hoods.<ref name=\"nrhpinv2\"/>\n\nThe house was built in 1865 for James B. Weaver, an [[Ohio]] native who settled in newly formed Bloomfield in 1847.  Politically active, he helped organize Iowa's [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], and served in the [[Union Army]] in the [[American Civil War]].  A champion of the rural farm electorate, he ran for [[President of the United States]] on the Greenback Party ticket in 1880, and the populist [[People's Party (United States)|People's Party]] in 1892, having helped form the party out of a group of reform-oriented organizations the previous year.<ref name=\"nrhpinv2\"/>\n\nWeaver lived in this house until 1890, when he moved to [[Des Moines, Iowa|Des Moines]].  After passing through several private owners, it was acquired by the Davis County Chautauqua Association, which operated it for a time as a [[historic house museum]].  It was eventually returned to private ownership,<ref name=\"nrhpinv2\"/> and is now operated as a bed and breakfast inn.\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category|James B. Weaver House (Bloomfield, Iowa)}}\n*[[List of National Historic Landmarks in Iowa]]\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Davis County, Iowa]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20171213092142/https://www.theweaverhouseinn.com/ James B. Weaver House Bed and Breakfast]\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places}}\n{{NRHP in Davis County, Iowa}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weaver, James B. House}}\n[[Category:National Historic Landmarks in Iowa]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Davis County, Iowa]]\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in Iowa]]\n[[Category:Houses in Davis County, Iowa]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1865]]\n[[Category:Bloomfield, Iowa]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:typo(s) fixed: President \u2192 president", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_B._Weaver_House"}
{"title_page": "500 yen coin", "text_new": "{{about|the current 500 yen coin|the former 500 yen banknote|500 yen note}}\n{{for|non-circulating commemorative coins of the same denomination|500 yen coin (commemorative)}}\n{{short description|Highest circulating denomination of Japanese yen coinage}}\n<!--<region-wp_meta media-type=\"text/yaml\">\n### main:\n###   - title:      500 yen coin\n###     keywords:   numismatics coin\n### review:\n###   - status: not-reviewed\n</region-wp_meta>\n-->\n{{Infobox Coin\n| Country = [[Japan]]\n| Denomination = Five hundred yen\n| Value = 500\n| Unit = [[Japanese yen]]\n| Mass = 7.00\n| Diameter = 26.5\n| Thickness = 2\n| Edge = Helically reeded edge\n| Composition = [[Nickel silver|Nickel-brass]] <br> 72% [[Copper|Cu]] <br> 20% [[Zinc|Zn]] <br> 8% [[Nickel|Ni]]\n| Years of Minting = 1982\u2013present\n| Catalog Number = y125\n| Obverse = 500 yen reverse.jpg\n| Obverse Design = [[Paulownia]]\n| Obverse Designer = -\n| Obverse Design Date = 2000\n| Reverse = 500_yen_obverse.jpg\n| Reverse Design = Denomination with [[Bamboo]] and [[Tachibana orange|tachibana]]\n| Reverse Designer = -\n| Reverse Design Date = 2000\n\n}}\n\nThe {{nihongo|'''500 yen coin'''|\u4e94\u767e\u5186\u786c\u8ca8|Gohyaku-en k\u014dka}} is the largest [[coin]] denomination of the [[Japanese yen]]. The 500 yen coin was first minted in 1982, with the current design being introduced in 2000. The coin ultimately replaced the [[500 yen note|500 yen paper note]].\n\n== History ==\n\nThe 500 yen coin was first minted in 1982 to replace the [[500 yen note]], which continued to be used alongside it until April 1, 1994. Soon, it became the victim of [[counterfeiting]], as neighboring [[South Korea]] introduced its 500 [[South Korean won|won]] coin the same year and could be easily modified to the exact weight of the \u00a5500 coin. As the \u20a9500 coin was roughly one-tenth the value of the \u00a5500 coin, these modified coins could be used at [[vending machine]]s to produce a profit.<ref>[http://archive.metropolis.co.jp/MoneyTalks/333/moneytalksinc.htm Metropolis [Tokyo&#93; Money Talks: Short Changed<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The \u20a9500 coin was slightly heavier than the \u00a5500 coin, whilst having exactly the same diameter and metal alloy, meaning that counterfeiters would use them as [[slug (coin)|slugs]] by drilling small holes on the surface of the coin to reduce its weight and fool vending machines which relied on weight to identify the coins.<ref>[http://dokdo-research.com/koreancoins.html The Contemporary \"Won\" Coins of the Republic of Korea (1966 - Present)] Dokdo Research (dokdo-research.com). Retrieved on 2017-05-05.</ref>\n\nA new design was minted in 2000. [[Zinc]] was added to give it a distinctive [[electrical conductivity]], its weight was reduced 0.2&nbsp;[[gram]]s, and a latent image was added to the zeros on the obverse. When viewed at an angle, \"500\u5186\" is printed vertically in each zero. When viewed at a different angle, a bar can be seen running down the inside of each zero. This bar is narrower than the \"500\u5186\" text.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071031113414/http://www.mint.go.jp/eng/operations/coin/new500-01.html Japan Mint: Analyzing 500 yen Nickel-brass Coin]</ref> [[Microprinting]] reading \"Nippon\" is found on both the obverse and reverse of the coin.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://madeira.cc.hokudai.ac.jp/RD/artifex/500YenCoin/index.html |title=Micro Characters on New 500-Yen Coin Found !!<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2007-02-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070807223618/http://madeira.cc.hokudai.ac.jp/RD/artifex/500YenCoin/index.html |archive-date=2007-08-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Within the span of a few years, vending machines were replaced by new models by manufacturers which verified coins based on electrical conductivity; while the old style 500 yen coins are still in circulation, many vending machines no longer accept them.\n\nIn 2019, the Bank of Japan unveiled a new version of the 500 yen coin. Now a [[bi-metallic coin]], with a [[Cupronickel|Copper-nickel]] center plug and a [[Nickel silver|Nickel-brass]] outer ring (the two compositions used in commemorative bi-metallic 500 yen coins), this version includes mirco-lettering and two alternating types of reeding on the edge of the coin. It is set to be issued in 2021.<ref>[https://www.boj.or.jp/announcements/release_2019/rel190409a.pdf \u65e5\u672c\u9280\u884c\u5238\u306e\u6539\u5237\u304a\u3088\u3073 500 \u5186\u8ca8\u306e\u6539\u92f3\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066] [[Bank of Japan]] (www.boj.or.jp). Retrieved on 2019-04-09.</ref>\n\nDespite these anti-counterfeiting measures, the coin is still the target of counterfeiters in Japan.\n\n==Designs==\n<gallery>\nFile:500yen-S57.jpg|[[Cupronickel|Copper-nickel]] version (1982\u20131999)\nFile:500yen-H12.jpg|[[Nickel silver|Nickel-brass]] version (2000\u2013present)\n</gallery>\n\n==Circulation figures==\n\n===Sh\u014dwa===\n\nThe following are circulation dates which cover Emperor [[Hirohito]]'s reign. The dates below correspond with the 57th to the 64th year (last) of his reign. Coins for this period will all begin with the Japanese symbol [[Sh\u014dwa period|\u662d\u548c]] (Sh\u014dwa).\n\n*Japanese coins are read with a left to right format: \n:\"Emperors name\" \u2192 \"Number representing year of reign\" \u2192 \"Year\" (Ex: \u662d\u548c \u2192 \u4e94\u5341\u516b \u2192 \u5e74).\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year of reign\n! [[Japanese calendar|Japanese date]]\n! [[Gregorian calendar|Gregorian date]]\n! Mintage<ref name=\"circulation\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mint.go.jp/WP_Vjp4V33Q/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/nenmeibetsuH31.R1.pdf|title=\u5e74\u9298\u5225\u8ca8\u5e63\u88fd\u9020\u679a\u6570|publisher=[[Japan Mint]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref>{{efn|name=mintage|Mintages on the Japan Mint website are in thousands}}\n|-\n| 57th\n| \u4e94\u5341\u4e03\n| 1982\n| 300,000,000\n|-\n| 58th\n| \u4e94\u5341\u516b\n| 1983\n| 240,000,000\n|-\n| 59th\n| \u4e94\u5341\u4e5d\n| 1984\n| 342,850,000\n|-\n| 60th\n| \u516d\u5341\n| 1985\n| 97,150,000\n|-\n| 61st\n| \u516d\u5341\u4e00\n| 1986\n| 49,960,000\n|-\n| 62nd\n| \u516d\u5341\u4e8c \n| 1987\n| 2,775,000\n|-\n| 63rd\n| \u516d\u5341\u4e09 \n| 1988\n| 148,218,000\n|-\n| 64th\n| \u516d\u5341\u56db \n| 1989\n| 16,042,000\n|}\n\n===Heisei===\n\nThe following are circulation dates in the reign of Emperor [[Akihito]], who was crowned in 1989. Coins for this period all begin with the Japanese symbol [[Heisei period|\u5e73\u6210]] (Heisei).\n\n*Japanese coins are read with a left to right format: \n:\"Emperors name\" \u2192 \"Number representing year of reign\" \u2192 \"Year\" (Ex: \u5e73\u6210 \u2192 \u4e94 \u2192 \u5e74).\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year of reign\n! [[Japanese calendar|Japanese date]]\n! [[Gregorian calendar|Gregorian date]]\n! Mintage<ref name=\"circulation\"/>{{efn|name=mintage}}\n|-\n| 1st\n| \u5143 \n| 1989\n| 192,852,000\n|-\n| 2nd\n| \u4e8c\n| 1990\n| 159,953,000\n|-\n| 3rd\n| \u4e09\n| 1991\n| 170,120,000\n|-\n| 4th\n| \u56db\n| 1992\n| 88,130,000\n|-\n| 5th\n| \u4e94\n| 1993\n| 132,240,000\n|-\n| 6th\n| \u516d\n| 1994\n| 105,772,000\n|-\n| 7th\n| \u4e03\n| 1995\n| 182,869,000\n|-\n| 8th\n| \u516b\n| 1996\n| 99,213,000\n|-\n| 9th\n| \u4e5d\n| 1997\n| 173,090,000\n|-\n| 10th\n| \u5341 \n| 1998\n| 214,608,000\n|-\n| 11th\n| \u5341\u4e00 \n| 1999\n| 165,120,000\n|-\n| 12th\n| \u5341\u4e8c\n| 2000\n| 595,969,000\n|-\n| 13th\n| \u5341\u4e09\n| 2001\n| 608,051,000\n|-\n| 14th\n| \u5341\u56db\n| 2002\n| 504,661,000\n|-\n| 15th\n| \u5341\u4e94\n| 2003\n| 438,405,000\n|-\n| 16th\n| \u5341\u516d\n| 2004\n| 356,903,000\n|-\n| 17th\n| \u5341\u4e03\n| 2005\n| 345,030,000\n|-\n| 18th\n| \u5341\u516b\n| 2006\n| 381,593,000\n|-\n| 19th\n| \u5341\u4e5d\n| 2007\n| 409,903,000\n|-\n| 20th\n| \u4e8c\u5341\n| 2008\n| 432,811,000\n|-\n| 21st\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u4e00\n| 2009\n| 343,003,000\n|-\n| 22nd\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u4e8c\n| 2010\n| 406,905,000\n|-\n| 23rd\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u4e09\n| 2011\n| 301,936,000\n|-\n| 24h\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u56db\n| 2012\n| 267,211,000\n|-\n| 25th\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u4e94\n| 2013\n| 137,892,000\n|-\n| 26th\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u516d\n| 2014\n| 167,013,000\n|-\n| 27th\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u4e03\n| 2015\n| 143,004,000\n|-\n| 28th\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u516b\n| 2016\n| 221,064,000\n|-\n| 29th\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u4e5d\n| 2017\n| 426,327,000\n|-\n| 30th\n| \u4e09\u5341\n| 2018\n| 286,192,000\n|-\n| 31st\n| {{lang|ja|\u4e09\u5341\u4e00}}\n| 2019\n| 126,164,000\n|}\n\n===Reiwa===\nThe following are circulation dates in the reign of the current Emperor. [[Naruhito]]'s [[Enthronement of the Japanese Emperor|accession]] to the [[Crysanthemum Throne]] took place on May 1, 2019 and he was formally enthroned on October 22, 2019. Coins for this period all begin with the Japanese symbol [[Reiwa period|\u4ee4\u548c]] (Reiwa). The inaugural year coin (2019) was marked \u5143 (first) and debuted during the summer of that year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Reiwa coins to debut summer 2019|url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20190403/p2a/00m/0na/013000c| }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year of reign\n! class=\"unsortable\"| [[Japanese calendar|Japanese date]]\n! [[Gregorian calendar|Gregorian date]]\n! Mintage<ref name=\"circulation\"/>{{efn|name=mintage}}\n|-\n| 1st\n| \u5143\n| 2019\n| 76,956,000\n|-\n| 2nd\n| \u4e8c\n| 2020\n| TBD\n|}\n\n==Collectability==\nMost of the 500 yen coins made for circulation are worth only their face value due to high mintage figures throughout their history. Notable exceptions occurred during the end of Emperor Sh\u014dwa's ([[Hirohito]]'s) reign when these figures fell. The [[key date]]s to the series are coins made during 1987 and 1989 (year 62 and 64) as both mintages are the lowest in the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kosen-kantei.jp/varity/premier-coins/|title=\u3010\u4fdd\u5b58\u7248\u3011\u30d7\u30ec\u30df\u30a2\u786c\u8ca8\u306e\u7a2e\u985e\u4e00\u89a7\uff01\u8cb7\u53d6\u4fa1\u683c\u30fb\u4fa1\u5024\u30fb\u5e73\u5747\u76f8\u5834\u307e\u3068\u3081|work=Kosen-kantei|language=Japanese|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> Sh\u014dwa's last year of reign also lasted only a week, making the year 64 dated coin popular among collectors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ngccoin.com/price-guide/world/japan-500-yen-y-87-yr-57(1982)-yr-64(1989)-cuid-54456-duid-147815|title=Japan 500 Yen Y#87 Yr.57(1982)-Yr.64(1989)|publisher=[[Numismatic Guaranty Corporation]]|accessdate=August 28, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"key dates\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kosenkaitori.net/s6264-500/|title=\u662d\u548c62\u5e74\u30fb\u662d\u548c64\u5e74\u306e500\u5186\u7389\u306e\u4fa1\u5024\u306f\uff1f\u6c17\u306b\u306a\u308b\u8cb7\u53d6\u4fa1\u683c\u3068\u30aa\u30b9\u30b9\u30e1\u696d\u8005\u3092\u3054\u7d39\u4ecb\uff01|work=Kosenkaitori|language=Japanese|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> These two coins sell for a premium online and through coin dealers depending on their condition.<ref name=\"key dates\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://financial-field.com/living/2019/08/06/entry-53023|title=10\u5186\u7389\u3060\u3051\u306950\u5186\u4ee5\u4e0a\u306e\u4fa1\u5024\u304c\u3042\u308b\u304b\u3082\uff01\u786c\u8ca8\u306b\u30d7\u30ec\u30df\u30a2\u30e0\u304c\u4ed8\u304f\u30ec\u30a2\u5ea6\u3068\u306f\uff1f|author=Shinichi Ueno|work=Financial Field|language=Japanese|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> It was also reported that collectors and the public alike kept year 31 (2019) coins of all denominations as \"Heisei Memorials\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://moneylab.f-academy.jp/column/education/23515/|title=\u65b0\u5143\u53f7\u5909\u66f4\u3001\u5e73\u621031\u5e74\u786c\u8ca8\u306b\u30d7\u30ec\u30df\u30a2\u306f\u3064\u304f\u306e\u304b\uff1f|work=Moneylab|date=March 19, 2019|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Portal|Japan|Money|Numismatics}}\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{commons category|500 yen coins}}\n\n{{Japanese currency and coinage}}\n\n[[Category:Coins of Japan]]\n[[Category:Japanese yen]]\n[[Category:Five-hundred-base-unit coins]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the current 500 yen coin|the former 500 yen banknote|500 yen note}}\n{{for|non-circulating commemorative coins of the same denomination|500 yen coin (commemorative)}}\n{{short description|Highest circulating denomination of Japanese yen coinage}}\n<!--<region-wp_meta media-type=\"text/yaml\">\n### main:\n###   - title:      500 yen coin\n###     keywords:   numismatics coin\n### review:\n###   - status: not-reviewed\n</region-wp_meta>\n-->\n{{Infobox Coin\n| Country = [[Japan]]\n| Denomination = Five hundred yen\n| Value = 500\n| Unit = [[Japanese yen]]\n| Mass = 7.00\n| Diameter = 26.5\n| Thickness = 2\n| Edge = Helically reeded edge\n| Composition = [[Nickel silver|Nickel-brass]] <br> 72% [[Copper|Cu]] <br> 20% [[Zinc|Zn]] <br> 8% [[Nickel|Ni]]\n| Years of Minting = 1982\u2013present\n| Catalog Number = y125\n| Obverse = 500 yen reverse.jpg\n| Obverse Design = [[Paulownia]]\n| Obverse Designer = -\n| Obverse Design Date = 2000\n| Reverse = 500_yen_obverse.jpg\n| Reverse Design = Denomination with [[Bamboo]] and [[Tachibana orange|tachibana]]\n| Reverse Designer = -\n| Reverse Design Date = 2000\n\n}}\n\nThe {{nihongo|'''500 yen coin'''|\u4e94\u767e\u5186\u786c\u8ca8|Gohyaku-en k\u014dka}} is the largest [[coin]] denomination of the [[Japanese yen]]. The 500 yen coin was first minted in 1982, with the current design being introduced in 2000. The coin ultimately replaced the [[500 yen note|500 yen paper note]].\n\n== History ==\n\nThe 500 yen coin was first minted in 1982 to replace the [[500 yen note]], which continued to be used alongside it until April 1, 1994. Soon, it became the victim of [[counterfeiting]], as neighboring [[South Korea]] introduced its 500 [[South Korean won|won]] coin the same year and could be easily modified to the exact weight of the \u00a5500 coin. As the \u20a9500 coin was roughly one-tenth the value of the \u00a5500 coin, these modified coins could be used at [[vending machine]]s to produce a profit.<ref>[http://archive.metropolis.co.jp/MoneyTalks/333/moneytalksinc.htm Metropolis [Tokyo&#93; Money Talks: Short Changed<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The \u20a9500 coin was slightly heavier than the \u00a5500 coin, whilst having exactly the same diameter and metal alloy, meaning that counterfeiters would use them as [[slug (coin)|slugs]] by drilling small holes on the surface of the coin to reduce its weight and fool vending machines which relied on weight to identify the coins.<ref>[http://dokdo-research.com/koreancoins.html The Contemporary \"Won\" Coins of the Republic of Korea (1966 - Present)] Dokdo Research (dokdo-research.com). Retrieved on 2017-05-05.</ref>\n\nA new design was minted in 2000. [[Zinc]] was added to give it a distinctive [[electrical conductivity]], its weight was reduced 0.2&nbsp;[[gram]]s, and a latent image was added to the zeros on the obverse. When viewed at an angle, \"500\u5186\" is printed vertically in each zero. When viewed at a different angle, a bar can be seen running down the inside of each zero. This bar is narrower than the \"500\u5186\" text.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071031113414/http://www.mint.go.jp/eng/operations/coin/new500-01.html Japan Mint: Analyzing 500 yen Nickel-brass Coin]</ref> [[Microprinting]] reading \"Nippon\" is found on both the obverse and reverse of the coin.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://madeira.cc.hokudai.ac.jp/RD/artifex/500YenCoin/index.html |title=Micro Characters on New 500-Yen Coin Found !!<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2007-02-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070807223618/http://madeira.cc.hokudai.ac.jp/RD/artifex/500YenCoin/index.html |archive-date=2007-08-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Within the span of a few years, vending machines were replaced by new models by manufacturers which verified coins based on electrical conductivity; while the old style 500 yen coins are still in circulation, many vending machines no longer accept them.\n\nIn 2019, the Bank of Japan unveiled a new version of the 500 yen coin. Now a [[bi-metallic coin]], with a [[Cupronickel|Copper-nickel]] center plug and a [[Nickel silver|Nickel-brass]] outer ring (the two compositions used in commemorative bi-metallic 500 yen coins), this version includes mirco-lettering and two alternating types of reeding on the edge of the coin. It is set to be issued in 2021.<ref>[https://www.boj.or.jp/announcements/release_2019/rel190409a.pdf \u65e5\u672c\u9280\u884c\u5238\u306e\u6539\u5237\u304a\u3088\u3073 500 \u5186\u8ca8\u306e\u6539\u92f3\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066] [[Bank of Japan]] (www.boj.or.jp). Retrieved on 2019-04-09.</ref>\n\nDespite these anti-counterfeiting measures, the coin is still the target of counterfeiters in Japan.\n\n==Designs==\n<gallery>\nFile:500yen-S57.jpg|[[Cupronickel|Copper-nickel]] version (1982\u20131999)\nFile:500yen-H12.jpg|[[Nickel silver|Nickel-brass]] version (2000\u2013present)\n</gallery>\n\n==Circulation figures==\n\n===Sh\u014dwa===\n\nThe following are circulation dates which cover Emperor [[Hirohito]]'s reign. The dates below correspond with the 57th to the 64th year (last) of his reign. Coins for this period will all begin with the Japanese symbol [[Sh\u014dwa period|\u662d\u548c]] (Sh\u014dwa).\n\n*Japanese coins are read with a left to right format: \n:\"Emperors name\" \u2192 \"Number representing year of reign\" \u2192 \"Year\" (Ex: \u662d\u548c \u2192 \u4e94\u5341\u516b \u2192 \u5e74).\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year of reign\n! [[Japanese calendar|Japanese date]]\n! [[Gregorian calendar|Gregorian date]]\n! Mintage<ref name=\"circulation\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mint.go.jp/WP_Vjp4V33Q/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/nenmeibetsuH31.R1.pdf|title=\u5e74\u9298\u5225\u8ca8\u5e63\u88fd\u9020\u679a\u6570|publisher=[[Japan Mint]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref>{{efn|name=mintage|Mintages on the Japan Mint website are in thousands}}\n|-\n| 57th\n| \u4e94\u5341\u4e03\n| 1982\n| 300,000,000\n|-\n| 58th\n| \u4e94\u5341\u516b\n| 1983\n| 240,000,000\n|-\n| 59th\n| \u4e94\u5341\u4e5d\n| 1984\n| 342,850,000\n|-\n| 60th\n| \u516d\u5341\n| 1985\n| 97,150,000\n|-\n| 61st\n| \u516d\u5341\u4e00\n| 1986\n| 49,960,000\n|-\n| 62nd\n| \u516d\u5341\u4e8c \n| 1987\n| 2,775,000\n|-\n| 63rd\n| \u516d\u5341\u4e09 \n| 1988\n| 148,218,000\n|-\n| 64th\n| \u516d\u5341\u56db \n| 1989\n| 16,042,000\n|}\n\n===Heisei===\n\nThe following are circulation dates in the reign of Emperor [[Akihito]], who was crowned in 1989. Coins for this period all begin with the Japanese symbol [[Heisei period|\u5e73\u6210]] (Heisei).\n\n*Japanese coins are read with a left to right format: \n:\"Emperors name\" \u2192 \"Number representing year of reign\" \u2192 \"Year\" (Ex: \u5e73\u6210 \u2192 \u4e94 \u2192 \u5e74).\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year of reign\n! [[Japanese calendar|Japanese date]]\n! [[Gregorian calendar|Gregorian date]]\n! Mintage<ref name=\"circulation\"/>{{efn|name=mintage}}\n|-\n| 1st\n| \u5143 \n| 1989\n| 192,852,000\n|-\n| 2nd\n| \u4e8c\n| 1990\n| 159,953,000\n|-\n| 3rd\n| \u4e09\n| 1991\n| 170,120,000\n|-\n| 4th\n| \u56db\n| 1992\n| 88,130,000\n|-\n| 5th\n| \u4e94\n| 1993\n| 132,240,000\n|-\n| 6th\n| \u516d\n| 1994\n| 105,772,000\n|-\n| 7th\n| \u4e03\n| 1995\n| 182,869,000\n|-\n| 8th\n| \u516b\n| 1996\n| 99,213,000\n|-\n| 9th\n| \u4e5d\n| 1997\n| 173,090,000\n|-\n| 10th\n| \u5341 \n| 1998\n| 214,608,000\n|-\n| 11th\n| \u5341\u4e00 \n| 1999\n| 165,120,000\n|-\n| 12th\n| \u5341\u4e8c\n| 2000\n| 595,969,000\n|-\n| 13th\n| \u5341\u4e09\n| 2001\n| 608,051,000\n|-\n| 14th\n| \u5341\u56db\n| 2002\n| 504,661,000\n|-\n| 15th\n| \u5341\u4e94\n| 2003\n| 438,405,000\n|-\n| 16th\n| \u5341\u516d\n| 2004\n| 356,903,000\n|-\n| 17th\n| \u5341\u4e03\n| 2005\n| 345,030,000\n|-\n| 18th\n| \u5341\u516b\n| 2006\n| 381,593,000\n|-\n| 19th\n| \u5341\u4e5d\n| 2007\n| 409,903,000\n|-\n| 20th\n| \u4e8c\u5341\n| 2008\n| 432,811,000\n|-\n| 21st\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u4e00\n| 2009\n| 343,003,000\n|-\n| 22nd\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u4e8c\n| 2010\n| 406,905,000\n|-\n| 23rd\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u4e09\n| 2011\n| 301,936,000\n|-\n| 24h\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u56db\n| 2012\n| 267,211,000\n|-\n| 25th\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u4e94\n| 2013\n| 137,892,000\n|-\n| 26th\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u516d\n| 2014\n| 167,013,000\n|-\n| 27th\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u4e03\n| 2015\n| 143,004,000\n|-\n| 28th\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u516b\n| 2016\n| 221,064,000\n|-\n| 29th\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u4e5d\n| 2017\n| 426,327,000\n|-\n| 30th\n| \u4e09\u5341\n| 2018\n| 286,192,000\n|-\n| 31st\n| {{lang|ja|\u4e09\u5341\u4e00}}\n| 2019\n| 126,164,000\n|}\n\n===Reiwa===\nThe following are circulation dates in the reign of the current Emperor. [[Naruhito]]'s [[Enthronement of the Japanese Emperor|accession]] to the [[Crysanthemum Throne]] took place on May 1, 2019 and he was formally enthroned on October 22, 2019. Coins for this period all begin with the Japanese symbol [[Reiwa period|\u4ee4\u548c]] (Reiwa). The inaugural year coin (2019) was marked \u5143 (first) and debuted during the summer of that year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Reiwa coins to debut summer 2019|url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20190403/p2a/00m/0na/013000c| }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year of reign\n! class=\"unsortable\"| [[Japanese calendar|Japanese date]]\n! [[Gregorian calendar|Gregorian date]]\n! Mintage<ref name=\"circulation\"/>{{efn|name=mintage}}\n|-\n| 1st\n| \u5143\n| 2019\n| 76,956,000\n|-\n| 2nd\n| \u4e8c\n| 2020\n| TBD\n|}\n\n==Collectability==\nMost of the 500 yen coins made for circulation are worth only their face value due to high mintage figures throughout their history. Notable exceptions occured during the end of Emperor Sh\u014dwa's ([[Hirohito]]'s) reign when these figures fell. The [[key date]]s to the series are coins made during 1987 and 1989 (year 62 and 64) as both mintages are the lowest in the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kosen-kantei.jp/varity/premier-coins/|title=\u3010\u4fdd\u5b58\u7248\u3011\u30d7\u30ec\u30df\u30a2\u786c\u8ca8\u306e\u7a2e\u985e\u4e00\u89a7\uff01\u8cb7\u53d6\u4fa1\u683c\u30fb\u4fa1\u5024\u30fb\u5e73\u5747\u76f8\u5834\u307e\u3068\u3081|work=Kosen-kantei|language=Japanese|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> Sh\u014dwa's last year of reign also lasted only a week, making the year 64 dated coin popular among collectors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ngccoin.com/price-guide/world/japan-500-yen-y-87-yr-57(1982)-yr-64(1989)-cuid-54456-duid-147815|title=Japan 500 Yen Y#87 Yr.57(1982)-Yr.64(1989)|publisher=[[Numismatic Guaranty Corporation]]|accessdate=August 28, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"key dates\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kosenkaitori.net/s6264-500/|title=\u662d\u548c62\u5e74\u30fb\u662d\u548c64\u5e74\u306e500\u5186\u7389\u306e\u4fa1\u5024\u306f\uff1f\u6c17\u306b\u306a\u308b\u8cb7\u53d6\u4fa1\u683c\u3068\u30aa\u30b9\u30b9\u30e1\u696d\u8005\u3092\u3054\u7d39\u4ecb\uff01|work=Kosenkaitori|language=Japanese|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> These two coins sell for a premium online and through coin dealers depending on their condition.<ref name=\"key dates\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://financial-field.com/living/2019/08/06/entry-53023|title=10\u5186\u7389\u3060\u3051\u306950\u5186\u4ee5\u4e0a\u306e\u4fa1\u5024\u304c\u3042\u308b\u304b\u3082\uff01\u786c\u8ca8\u306b\u30d7\u30ec\u30df\u30a2\u30e0\u304c\u4ed8\u304f\u30ec\u30a2\u5ea6\u3068\u306f\uff1f|author=Shinichi Ueno|work=Financial Field|language=Japanese|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> It was also reported that collectors and the public alike kept year 31 (2019) coins of all denominations as \"Heisei Memorials\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://moneylab.f-academy.jp/column/education/23515/|title=\u65b0\u5143\u53f7\u5909\u66f4\u3001\u5e73\u621031\u5e74\u786c\u8ca8\u306b\u30d7\u30ec\u30df\u30a2\u306f\u3064\u304f\u306e\u304b\uff1f|work=Moneylab|date=March 19, 2019|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Portal|Japan|Money|Numismatics}}\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{commons category|500 yen coins}}\n\n{{Japanese currency and coinage}}\n\n[[Category:Coins of Japan]]\n[[Category:Japanese yen]]\n[[Category:Five-hundred-base-unit coins]]\n", "name_user": "Vanisaac", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correcting spelling: occured->occurred", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/500_yen_coin"}
{"title_page": "Wildcliff", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP | name = Wildcliff\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = Wildcliff, 42 ,Wildcliff Rd., New Rochelle, Westchester County, New York.JPG\n  | caption = Wildcliff in 2014\n  | location= 42 Wildcliff Road, [[New Rochelle, New York]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|40|54|23|N|73|46|12|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = \n  | area =\n  | built =1852\n  | architect= Alexander Jackson Davis\n  | architecture= Gothic Revival, Tudor Revival<ref>[http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=101366 National Register of Historic Places Registration Form description]</ref>\n  | added = December 31, 2002\n  | governing_body = Local\n  | refnum=02001656\n<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2008a}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Wildcliff''', also referred to as the '''Cyrus Lawton House''', was a historic residence overlooking [[Long Island Sound]] in [[New Rochelle, New York|New Rochelle]] in [[Westchester County, New York]]. This 20-room cottage-villa, built in about 1852, was designed by prominent architect [[Alexander Jackson Davis]] in the [[Gothic Revival]] style. The home was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on December 31, 2002.<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2008a}}</ref>\n\nThe unoccupied mansion was destroyed by a suspicious fire on the evening of November 26, 2018. The house was a total loss.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/Historic-Mansion-Fire-Wildcliff-Cyrus-Lawton-House-New-Rochelle-Westchester-501280931.html|title=Historic Mansion in New Rochelle Goes Up in Flames|work=NBC New York|access-date=2018-11-27|language=en}}</ref><ref>https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2018/11/26/historic-new-rochelle-mansion-burns-down-in-suspicious-fire/</ref>  On December 12, 2018, four 13-year old, middle school boys (all local, New Rochelle residents) were arrested and charged in connection with the fire. All were charged as juveniles with misdemeanor third-degree criminal trespass, while one faces a felony charge of fourth-degree arson.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lohud.com/story/news/crime/2018/12/12/teens-arrested-wildcliff-mansion-fire-arson/2289023002/|title=Four teens arrested in Wildcliff mansion fire|work=Rockland/Westchester Journal News|access-date=2018-12-12|language=en}}</ref>\n[[File:Wildcliff Aftermath.jpg|thumb|The Wildcliff Mansion after a three-alarm fire destroyed it. Image taken on November 27th, 2018.]]\n\n==Overview==\nDesigned in 1852 by Alexander Jackson Davis, one of the preeminent American architects of the nineteenth century, the house was sited to take full advantage of the dramatic views of the water. Davis\u2019 original plan envisioned the family sitting on the villa's front porch and looking out over the spectacular scenery. The beauty of the house and its site were accented by the progression of the entry drive. The visitor originally entered the property from the north along a private road. The curving drive ascended toward the house, proceeding toward Echo Bay and curving around to the front door. The family who first commissioned the design was one Cyrus Lawton, a close friend of Mr. Davis. Mrs. Lawton was a member of the prominent Davenport family, for whom the entire area is named, and the house was a wedding gift to the couple.<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9D00E2D6103DEE32A25754C0A9639C946397D6CF Cyrus Lawton Obituary], ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref>\n\nWildcliff was erected in the early 1850s, during a period when New Rochelle was beginning its transformation from a rural farming community into a residential suburb. Improvements in transportation permitted affluent families to build homes in New Rochelle and commute to work in nearby New York City. The land along the scenic north shore of [[Long Island Sound]] was especially sought after and many of Davis' designs were built here. His smaller homes were called \"''cottages''\", and the more substantial ones \"''villas''\", however the terms were frequently combined. Among their typical features were prominent, steep-roofed [[gable]]s, with elaborately carved [[bargeboard]]s under their [[eaves]].<ref>A. J. Davis and the Gothic Revival, Edna Donnell, Metropolitan Museum Studies, Vol. 5, No. 2 (Sep., 1936)</ref> Wildcliff is one of two \"''cottage-villas''\" built by Davis on New Rochelle's waterfront peninsula, [[Davenport Neck (New York)|Davenport Neck]], the other being [[Davenport House (New Rochelle, New York)|\"Sans Souci\"]] (or Davenport House).<ref>[http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=101366 National Register of Historic Places Registration Form], section 8, page 2</ref>\n\nAfter Cyrus Lawton's death in 1902, the property was inherited by his son Newberry Lawton Davenport. It was later purchased by Julius and Clara Prince who moved into the home in 1914. Clara Prince donated Wildcliff to the City of New Rochelle in 1940 with the hopes that it would be used as a natural [[science museum]].<ref>\"Wildcliff Youth Museum\", manuscript printed by the City of New Rochelle, in collection of New Rochelle Public Library (New Rochelle Museums - Wildcliff File)</ref> Clara Prince's obituary, \"Mrs. Julius Prince\", ''The New York Times'', September 14, 1941, page 49, notes that she was a \"philanthropist who had given generously to educational projects\" and that she was especially known for the donation of Wildcliff to New Rochelle in 1940, ten years after the city had tried in vain to purchase the property. It has since been used for a variety of purposes including a youth museum and [[performing arts center]].<ref>[http://noambramson.org/publicdocs/2008-10/Preserver.pdf The Preserver - Highlighting New Rochelle's Rich Past]</ref> Around 1970 a wing housing a theater was added at one corner of the house but the main structure remains intact.<ref>[http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=101366 National Register of Historic Places Registration Form], section 8, page 7</ref>\n\nSince late 2010, the local organization Jen's Community at Wildcliff has been working with the City of New Rochelle and its citizens to bring awareness to the building and to create a [[preschool]] and education center.<ref name=\"JCW\">[http://www.jenscommunityatwildcliff.org Jen's Community at Wildcliff]></ref>\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:Wildcliff, 42 Wildcliff Rd., New Rochelle, Westchester County, New York..JPG|thumb|right|detail]]\nWildcliff is a 2\u00bd-story house faced primarily in rubblestone of various colors. These stones give the picturesque design a natural quality, as if the building were rising out of the landscape. For a house in the Northeast, Downing prescribed a design with high roofs, thick walls, warm rooms, and chimneys. The original front facade of the building was on the southern portion of the present house facing Long Island Sound, now partially obscured by the out-of-character one story addition used as a theater. This facade originally had a 2\u00bd-story central gable with a pair of windows on the first\nstory looking out over the water. In the mid 1860s, Davis designed additions to the house in the same style with special efforts made so that the changes would be as inconspicuous as possible. Bargeboards and other ornamental details match exactly and stonework was laid so that there would be no sign of the joint between the old and new sections.<ref>[http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=101366 National Register of Historic Places Registration Form], section 8, page 7</ref><ref name=Hershenson>Roberta Hershenson, [https://www.nytimes.com/2006/03/26/nyregion/nyregionspecial2/26wethea.html Vision Takes On Reality as Group Inches Closer to a Stage of Its Own], The New York Times, March 26, 2006</ref><ref name=grant>[http://nysparks.state.ny.us/news/press/view.asp?pressID=573 2006 EPF Grant Awards], Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation, October 20, 2006</ref><ref name=\"regform\">{{cite web|author=Andrew S. Dolkart and Peter D. Shaver |title=National Register of Historic Places Registration:  Wildcliff / Cyrus Lawton House |url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=101366 |date=June 3, 2002 |accessdate=2010-06-19 |publisher=[[New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation]]}} and [http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=101368 ''Accompanying 6 photos, exterior and interior, from 2002'']</ref>\n\nLater owners Julius and Clara Prince were responsible for the second major expansion to the home which was done in the half-timbered [[Tudor architecture|Tudor]] style. The additions consisted of the construction of a [[porte-cochere]], a new entrance on the south facade of the home, and the conversion of the original entrance into a long, twelve-part window.<ref>[http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=101366 National Register of Historic Places Registration Form], section 8, page 6</ref>\n \nThe original plan of the house can still be read on the interior. To the south is the original library and entrance hall, now combined into one space. On the upper floors are bedrooms with steeply sloping walls reflecting their locations within the gables. The attic retains some original floorboards and four paneled doors with original knobs. The interior retains much of its historic plan and some historic fittings, but much of the interior detail has been lost.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Commonscat|Wildcliff (New Rochelle, New York)}}\n* Davis, Alexander Jackson, ''Day Book'' vol. 2, October 1853 - December 1869 (collection Columbia University, Avery Library)\n* Davis, Alexander Jackson, ''Diary''' [Journal] (collection Metropolitan Museum of Art, Department of Prints and Drawings)\n* Peck, Amelia, ed., ''Alexander Jackson Davis: American Architect 1803 - 1892''. New York: Metropolitan Museum of Art and Rizzoli, 1992.\n\n{{New Rochelle, New York}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New York}}\n\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in New Rochelle, New York]]\n[[Category:Gothic Revival architecture in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1852]]\n[[Category:Houses in Westchester County, New York]]\n[[Category:Alexander Jackson Davis buildings]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Westchester County, New York]]\n[[Category:1852 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP | name = Wildcliff\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = Wildcliff, 42 ,Wildcliff Rd., New Rochelle, Westchester County, New York.JPG\n  | caption = Wildcliff in 2014\n  | location= 42 Wildcliff Road, [[New Rochelle, New York]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|40|54|23|N|73|46|12|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = \n  | area =\n  | built =1852\n  | architect= Alexander Jackson Davis\n  | architecture= Gothic Revival, Tudor Revival<ref>[http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=101366 National Register of Historic Places Registration Form description]</ref>\n  | added = December 31, 2002\n  | governing_body = Local\n  | refnum=02001656\n<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2008a}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Wildcliff''', also referred to as the '''Cyrus Lawton House''', was a historic residence overlooking [[Long Island Sound]] in [[New Rochelle, New York|New Rochelle]] in [[Westchester County, New York]]. This 20-room cottage-villa, built in about 1852, was designed by prominent architect [[Alexander Jackson Davis]] in the [[Gothic Revival]] style. The home was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on December 31, 2002.<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2008a}}</ref>\n\nThe unoccupied mansion was destroyed by a suspicious fire on the evening of November 26, 2018. The house was a total loss.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/Historic-Mansion-Fire-Wildcliff-Cyrus-Lawton-House-New-Rochelle-Westchester-501280931.html|title=Historic Mansion in New Rochelle Goes Up in Flames|work=NBC New York|access-date=2018-11-27|language=en}}</ref><ref>https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2018/11/26/historic-new-rochelle-mansion-burns-down-in-suspicious-fire/</ref>  On December 12, 2018 four 13-year old, middle school boys (all local, New Rochelle residents) were arrested and charged in connection with the fire. All were charged as juveniles with misdemeanor third-degree criminal trespass, while one faces a felony charge of fourth-degree arson.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lohud.com/story/news/crime/2018/12/12/teens-arrested-wildcliff-mansion-fire-arson/2289023002/|title=Four teens arrested in Wildcliff mansion fire|work=Rockland/Westchester Journal News|access-date=2018-12-12|language=en}}</ref>\n[[File:Wildcliff Aftermath.jpg|thumb|The Wildcliff Mansion after a three-alarm fire destroyed it. Image taken on November 27th, 2018.]]\n\n==Overview==\nDesigned in 1852 by Alexander Jackson Davis, one of the preeminent American architects of the nineteenth century, the house was sited to take full advantage of the dramatic views of the water. Davis\u2019 original plan envisioned the family sitting on the villa's front porch and looking out over the spectacular scenery. The beauty of the house and its site were accented by the progression of the entry drive. The visitor originally entered the property from the north along a private road. The curving drive ascended toward the house, proceeding toward Echo Bay and curving around to the front door. The family who first commissioned the design was one Cyrus Lawton, a close friend of Mr. Davis. Mrs. Lawton was a member of the prominent Davenport family, for whom the entire area is named, and the house was a wedding gift to the couple.<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9D00E2D6103DEE32A25754C0A9639C946397D6CF Cyrus Lawton Obituary], ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref>\n\nWildcliff was erected in the early 1850s, during a period when New Rochelle was beginning its transformation from a rural farming community into a residential suburb. Improvements in transportation permitted affluent families to build homes in New Rochelle and commute to work in nearby New York City. The land along the scenic north shore of [[Long Island Sound]] was especially sought after and many of Davis' designs were built here. His smaller homes were called \"''cottages''\", and the more substantial ones \"''villas''\", however the terms were frequently combined. Among their typical features were prominent, steep-roofed [[gable]]s, with elaborately carved [[bargeboard]]s under their [[eaves]].<ref>A. J. Davis and the Gothic Revival, Edna Donnell, Metropolitan Museum Studies, Vol. 5, No. 2 (Sep., 1936)</ref> Wildcliff is one of two \"''cottage-villas''\" built by Davis on New Rochelle's waterfront peninsula, [[Davenport Neck (New York)|Davenport Neck]], the other being [[Davenport House (New Rochelle, New York)|\"Sans Souci\"]] (or Davenport House).<ref>[http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=101366 National Register of Historic Places Registration Form], section 8, page 2</ref>\n\nAfter Cyrus Lawton's death in 1902, the property was inherited by his son Newberry Lawton Davenport. It was later purchased by Julius and Clara Prince who moved into the home in 1914. Clara Prince donated Wildcliff to the City of New Rochelle in 1940 with the hopes that it would be used as a natural [[science museum]].<ref>\"Wildcliff Youth Museum\", manuscript printed by the City of New Rochelle, in collection of New Rochelle Public Library (New Rochelle Museums - Wildcliff File)</ref> Clara Prince's obituary, \"Mrs. Julius Prince\", ''The New York Times'', September 14, 1941, page 49, notes that she was a \"philanthropist who had given generously to educational projects\" and that she was especially known for the donation of Wildcliff to New Rochelle in 1940, ten years after the city had tried in vain to purchase the property. It has since been used for a variety of purposes including a youth museum and [[performing arts center]].<ref>[http://noambramson.org/publicdocs/2008-10/Preserver.pdf The Preserver - Highlighting New Rochelle's Rich Past]</ref> Around 1970 a wing housing a theater was added at one corner of the house but the main structure remains intact.<ref>[http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=101366 National Register of Historic Places Registration Form], section 8, page 7</ref>\n\nSince late 2010, the local organization Jen's Community at Wildcliff has been working with the City of New Rochelle and its citizens to bring awareness to the building and to create a [[preschool]] and education center.<ref name=\"JCW\">[http://www.jenscommunityatwildcliff.org Jen's Community at Wildcliff]></ref>\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:Wildcliff, 42 Wildcliff Rd., New Rochelle, Westchester County, New York..JPG|thumb|right|detail]]\nWildcliff is a 2\u00bd-story house faced primarily in rubblestone of various colors. These stones give the picturesque design a natural quality, as if the building were rising out of the landscape. For a house in the Northeast, Downing prescribed a design with high roofs, thick walls, warm rooms, and chimneys. The original front fa\u00e7ade of the building was on the southern portion of the present house facing Long Island Sound, now partially obscured by the out-of-character one story addition used as a theater. This facade originally had a 2\u00bd-story central gable with a pair of windows on the first\nstory looking out over the water. In the mid 1860s Davis designed additions to the house in the same style with special efforts made so that the changes would be as inconspicuous as possible. Bargeboards and other ornamental details match exactly and stonework was laid so that there would be no sign of the joint between the old and new sections.<ref>[http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=101366 National Register of Historic Places Registration Form], section 8, page 7</ref><ref name=Hershenson>Roberta Hershenson, [https://www.nytimes.com/2006/03/26/nyregion/nyregionspecial2/26wethea.html Vision Takes On Reality as Group Inches Closer to a Stage of Its Own], The New York Times, March 26, 2006</ref><ref name=grant>[http://nysparks.state.ny.us/news/press/view.asp?pressID=573 2006 EPF Grant Awards], Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation, October 20, 2006</ref><ref name=\"regform\">{{cite web|author=Andrew S. Dolkart and Peter D. Shaver |title=National Register of Historic Places Registration:  Wildcliff / Cyrus Lawton House |url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=101366 |date=June 3, 2002 |accessdate=2010-06-19 |publisher=[[New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation]]}} and [http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=101368 ''Accompanying 6 photos, exterior and interior, from 2002'']</ref>\n\nLater owners Julius and Clara Prince were responsible for the second major expansion to the home which was done in the half-timbered [[Tudor architecture|Tudor]] style. The additions consisted of the construction of a [[porte-cochere]], a new entrance on the south facade of the home, and the conversion of the original entrance into a long, twelve-part window.<ref>[http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=101366 National Register of Historic Places Registration Form], section 8, page 6</ref>\n \nThe original plan of the house can still be read on the interior. To the south is the original library and entrance hall, now combined into one space. On the upper floors are bedrooms with steeply sloping walls reflecting their locations within the gables. The attic retains some original floorboards and four paneled doors with original knobs. The interior retains much of its historic plan and some historic fittings, but much of the interior detail has been lost.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Commonscat|Wildcliff (New Rochelle, New York)}}\n* Davis, Alexander Jackson, ''Day Book'' vol. 2, October 1853 - December 1869 (collection Columbia University, Avery Library)\n* Davis, Alexander Jackson, ''Diary''' [Journal] (collection Metropolitan Museum of Art, Department of Prints and Drawings)\n* Peck, Amelia, ed., ''Alexander Jackson Davis: American Architect 1803 - 1892''. New York: Metropolitan Museum of Art and Rizzoli, 1992.\n\n{{New Rochelle, New York}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New York}}\n\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in New Rochelle, New York]]\n[[Category:Gothic Revival architecture in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1852]]\n[[Category:Houses in Westchester County, New York]]\n[[Category:Alexander Jackson Davis buildings]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Westchester County, New York]]\n[[Category:1852 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "YUEdits", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammar improvements", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wildcliff"}
{"title_page": "Ronald Wilson Reagan College Preparatory High School", "text_new": "\n\n{{refimprove|date=January 2017}}\n'''Ronald Wilson Reagan College Preparatory High School''' (RWR) is a [[high school]] located at 4965 South 20th Street in the Town of Lake neighborhood of [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin]], [[United States|USA]]. It is a part of [[Milwaukee Public Schools]] (MPS).\n\nFormerly known as Town of Lake College Preparatory High School, the school changed its name following the death of former President [[Ronald Reagan]] in June 2004. The renaming was approved by the Milwaukee Board of School Directors on September 29, 2004, with the official renaming ceremony taking place on June 3, 2005. Ronald Wilson Reagan College Preparatory High School became an [[International Baccalaureate]] (IB) World School. Reagan has an alternating day schedule.\n\n== History ==\n{{circa}}2004 it had 100 students. By 2010 it had 1,000 students, and so many students applied for admission that the school had a wait list.<ref>{{cite news|author=Borsuk, Alan J.|url=http://www.jsonline.com/news/education/82526017.html|title=Is success too much at Reagan school?|newspaper=[[Milwaukee Journal-Sentinel]]|date=2010-01-23|accessdate=2017-01-01|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20161212064317/http://www.jsonline.com/news/education/82526017.html|archivedate=2016-12-12}} <!--Original URL: http://www.jsonline.com/news/education/82526017.html--> - Scroll down to see the article</ref>\n\n== Administration ==\nThe principal of Reagan High School is Mike Roemer. The school has a staff of almost 100, ranging from special education instructors to subject matter teachers and [[International Baccalaureate]] coordinators.{{cn|date=October 2015}}\n\n== Academics ==\nRonald W. Reagan High School is an accredited International Baccalaureate Organization World School. The school offers IB credited classes to juniors and seniors.\n\nReagan's credit recovery program replaced its summer school program with an online program for students who have failed classes.\n\n== Academic resources ==\nReagan's Student Learning Community is an Internet resource that students use to access class information and presentations posted online by teachers.\n\nThe school library contains books, calculators, films, and other resources.\n\nReagan has a number of computers and laptops at the disposal of students.\n\n== Extracurricular activities==\nRonald Reagan has numerous different after school activities which include but are not limited to: Forensics, DJ Club, Radio Reagan, Debate, Art Club, Theater Club, International Club, Card Game Club, Husky Howler Newspaper, GSA (Gay/Straight Alliance), Metal Club, Math Club, Physics Club, Yes Club, Weightlifting Club, Spoken Word, Stage Crew, Student Council, Urban Promise, Black Student Union, Yearbook Staff, Bible Study Club, Four R's of Conservation, K-Pop Dance Club, Culinary Club, Competition Drum Line. \n\nReagan holds an annual pep rally in the first and second semester and a Black History and International Program. These programs are held during school hours and most are student run. Reagan's Talent Show is also student run, but it occurs after school. The school also holds an annual Reagan Film Festival, in which students who take the class IB Film present their films to an audience.\n\nReagan's music department includes ensembles like String Orchestra, Beginning Band, Intermediate Band, Advanced Band, Lower and Upperclassmen Jazz band, Marching band, Competition Drum Line, Treble Choir, Men's Choir, Concert Choir and Chamber Choir. The Reagan Chamber Choir recently{{when|date=October 2015}} went to State in the WSMA competition and performed for the superintendent of the Milwaukee Public Schools. The Marching band performs every year in the Milwaukee Holiday Parade. There are performances by the bands and choirs throughout the year after school in the auditorium.\n\n''The Husky Howler'', the school's official newspaper, was launched on December 3rd, 2013. The newspaper is updated monthly by extremely hard-working students and can be found online at http://www.thehuskyhowler.com. \n\n=== Musical theater ===\nReagan's musical program holds an annual musical at the end of January. Past performances have included ''School House Rock'', ''The Boyfriend'', ''Bye Bye Birdie'', and ''Joseph and his Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat''. The school also holds an annual program called \"Fall One Acts\", which showcases the work of Reagan's IB Theatre. The scripts are written and performed by students.\n\n=== Sports ===\nReagan varsity baseball was the conference champion for 2014 and 2015, and defeated Arrowhead High School to go to state in 2015 for the first time in school history. Reagan soccer  went to state in 2011.<!-- This section needs more info. -->\n\nReagan's sports teams include:\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em|content=\n* Cross country\n* Track and field\n* Golf\n* Wrestling\n* Spirit squad\n* Baseball: freshman, JV and varsity\n* Softball: JV and varsity\n* Basketball (Boys): freshman, JV and varsity\n* Basketball (Girls): freshman, JV and varsity\n* Football: JV and varsity\n* Soccer (Boys): JV1, JV2, varsity\n* Soccer (Girls): JV and varsity\n* Volleyball: freshman, JV and varsity\n* Tennis (Girls): JV and varsity\n* Tennis (Boys): JV and varsity\n* Swim (Boys): JV and varsity\n* Swim (Girls): JV and varsity\n}}\n\n==== Rufus King rivalry ====\nRufus King and Reagan have been rivals since the early 2000s. Rufus King is also an International Baccalaureate School and the two schools are often in competition for state ranking. The schools compete in sports as well as academics.\n\n== Sexual assault allegations ==\nIn December 2018, a Ronald Reagan high school teacher, Kenneth Chu, was arrested after police found out that he was using multiple fake social media accounts on Snapchat to chat with recent graduates from the school. It was brought to their attention after a 16 year old girl showed text messages between her and Chu to her parents. Chu asked the girl if she wanted to \"sneak off and fool around\", and sent naked photos of himself to the girl, threatening her with suspension if she did not send him photos of her of a similar nature. Police  found that he sent more than 40 nude pictures of himself to the girl. Chu was re-arrested in April 2019 and was sentenced to 4 years in prison in June 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Keene |first1=Lauren |title=Former Reagan High School teacher accused of sexual assault of a student sentenced to 4 years in prison |url=https://fox6now.com/2019/06/27/former-reagan-high-school-teacher-accused-of-sexual-assault-of-a-student-sentenced-to-4-years-in-prison/ |website=Fox6Now |accessdate=8 July 2019}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official|https://www.ronaldreaganhs.org/}}\n{{coord|42.953785|-87.940062|type:edu_globe:earth_region:US-WI|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:High schools in Milwaukee]]\n[[Category:International Baccalaureate schools in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials to Ronald Reagan|Reagan]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2004]]\n[[Category:2004 establishments in Wisconsin]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{refimprove|date=January 2017}}\n'''Ronald Wilson Reagan College Preparatory High School''' (RWR) is a [[high school]] located at 4965 South 20th Street in the Town of Lake neighborhood of [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin]], [[United States|USA]]. It is a part of [[Milwaukee Public Schools]] (MPS).\n\nFormerly known as Town of Lake College Preparatory High School, the school changed its name following the death of former President [[Ronald Reagan]] in June 2004. The renaming was approved by the Milwaukee Board of School Directors on September 29, 2004, with the official renaming ceremony taking place on June 3, 2005. Ronald Wilson Reagan College Preparatory High School became an [[International Baccalaureate]] (IB) World School. Reagan has an alternating day schedule.\n\n== History ==\n{{circa}}2004 it had 100 students. By 2010 it had 1,000 students, and so many students applied for admission that the school had a wait list.<ref>{{cite news|author=Borsuk, Alan J.|url=http://www.jsonline.com/news/education/82526017.html|title=Is success too much at Reagan school?|newspaper=[[Milwaukee Journal-Sentinel]]|date=2010-01-23|accessdate=2017-01-01|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20161212064317/http://www.jsonline.com/news/education/82526017.html|archivedate=2016-12-12}} <!--Original URL: http://www.jsonline.com/news/education/82526017.html--> - Scroll down to see the article</ref>\n\n== Administration ==\nThe principal of Reagan High School is Joshua Preston. The school has a staff of almost 100, ranging from special education instructors to subject matter teachers and [[International Baccalaureate]] coordinators.{{cn|date=October 2015}}\n\n== Academics ==\nRonald W. Reagan High School is an accredited International Baccalaureate Organization World School. The school offers IB credited classes to juniors and seniors.\n\nReagan's credit recovery program replaced its summer school program with an online program for students who have failed classes.\n\n== Academic resources ==\nReagan's Student Learning Community is an Internet resource that students use to access class information and presentations posted online by teachers.\n\nThe school library contains books, calculators, films, and other resources.\n\nReagan has a number of computers and laptops at the disposal of students.\n\n== Extracurricular activities==\nRonald Reagan has numerous different after school activities which include but are not limited to: Forensics, DJ Club, Radio Reagan, Debate, Art Club, Theater Club, International Club, Card Game Club, Husky Howler Newspaper, GSA (Gay/Straight Alliance), Metal Club, Math Club, Physics Club, Yes Club, Weightlifting Club, Spoken Word, Stage Crew, Student Council, Urban Promise, Black Student Union, Yearbook Staff, Bible Study Club, Four R's of Conservation, K-Pop Dance Club, Culinary Club, Competition Drum Line. \n\nReagan holds an annual pep rally in the first and second semester and a Black History and International Program. These programs are held during school hours and most are student run. Reagan's Talent Show is also student run, but it occurs after school. The school also holds an annual Reagan Film Festival, in which students who take the class IB Film present their films to an audience.\n\nReagan's music department includes ensembles like String Orchestra, Beginning Band, Intermediate Band, Advanced Band, Lower and Upperclassmen Jazz band, Marching band, Competition Drum Line, Treble Choir, Men's Choir, Concert Choir and Chamber Choir. The Reagan Chamber Choir recently{{when|date=October 2015}} went to State in the WSMA competition and performed for the superintendent of the Milwaukee Public Schools. The Marching band performs every year in the Milwaukee Holiday Parade. There are performances by the bands and choirs throughout the year after school in the auditorium.\n\n''The Husky Howler'', the school's official newspaper, was launched on December 3rd, 2013. The newspaper is updated monthly by extremely hard-working students and can be found online at http://www.thehuskyhowler.com. \n\n=== Musical theater ===\nReagan's musical program holds an annual musical at the end of January. Past performances have included ''School House Rock'', ''The Boyfriend'', ''Bye Bye Birdie'', and ''Joseph and his Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat''. The school also holds an annual program called \"Fall One Acts\", which showcases the work of Reagan's IB Theatre. The scripts are written and performed by students.\n\n=== Sports ===\nReagan varsity baseball was the conference champion for 2014 and 2015, and defeated Arrowhead High School to go to state in 2015 for the first time in school history. Reagan soccer  went to state in 2011.<!-- This section needs more info. -->\n\nReagan's sports teams include:\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em|content=\n* Cross country\n* Track and field\n* Golf\n* Wrestling\n* Spirit squad\n* Baseball: freshman, JV and varsity\n* Softball: JV and varsity\n* Basketball (Boys): freshman, JV and varsity\n* Basketball (Girls): freshman, JV and varsity\n* Football: JV and varsity\n* Soccer (Boys): JV1, JV2, varsity\n* Soccer (Girls): JV and varsity\n* Volleyball: freshman, JV and varsity\n* Tennis (Girls): JV and varsity\n* Tennis (Boys): JV and varsity\n* Swim (Boys): JV and varsity\n* Swim (Girls): JV and varsity\n}}\n\n==== Rufus King rivalry ====\nRufus King and Reagan have been rivals since the early 2000s. Rufus King is also an International Baccalaureate School and the two schools are often in competition for state ranking. The schools compete in sports as well as academics.\n\n== Sexual assault allegations ==\nIn December 2018, a Ronald Reagan high school teacher, Kenneth Chu, was arrested after police found out that he was using multiple fake social media accounts on Snapchat to chat with recent graduates from the school. It was brought to their attention after a 16 year old girl showed text messages between her and Chu to her parents. Chu asked the girl if she wanted to \"sneak off and fool around\", and sent naked photos of himself to the girl, threatening her with suspension if she did not send him photos of her of a similar nature. Police  found that he sent more than 40 nude pictures of himself to the girl. Chu was re-arrested in April 2019 and was sentenced to 4 years in prison in June 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Keene |first1=Lauren |title=Former Reagan High School teacher accused of sexual assault of a student sentenced to 4 years in prison |url=https://fox6now.com/2019/06/27/former-reagan-high-school-teacher-accused-of-sexual-assault-of-a-student-sentenced-to-4-years-in-prison/ |website=Fox6Now |accessdate=8 July 2019}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official|https://www.ronaldreaganhs.org/}}\n{{coord|42.953785|-87.940062|type:edu_globe:earth_region:US-WI|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:High schools in Milwaukee]]\n[[Category:International Baccalaureate schools in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials to Ronald Reagan|Reagan]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2004]]\n[[Category:2004 establishments in Wisconsin]]\n", "name_user": "2603:6000:a940:f5:305e:5920:7a67:e9ec", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eAdministration)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ronald_Wilson_Reagan_College_Preparatory_High_School"}
{"title_page": "June 2", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}{{calendar}}\n{{This date in recent years}}\n{{Day}}\n\n==Events==\n* [[455]] &ndash; [[Sack of Rome (455)|Sack of Rome]]: [[Vandals]] enter Rome, and plunder the city for two weeks.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/cambridgemediev00whitgoog |title=The Cambridge Medieval History |last=Gwatkin |first=Henry Melvill |last2=Whitney |first2=James Pounder |last3=Tanner |first3=Joseph Robson |last4=Previt\u00e9-Orton |first4=Charles William |last5=Brooke |first5=Zachary Nugent |publisher=Macmillan |year=1911 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/cambridgemediev00whitgoog/page/n366 308] |display-authors=2 |quote=On 2 June Gaiseric marched into Rome ... The Vandals stayed a fortnight...}}</ref>\n*[[1098]] &ndash; [[First Crusade]]: The first [[Siege of Antioch]] ends as Crusader forces take the city; the second siege began five days later.<ref>{{cite book |chapter=The Gateway to the Middle East: Antioch, 1098 |title=Special Operations in the Age of Chivalry, 1100\u20131550 |first=Yuval Noah |last=Harari| authorlink=Yuval Noah Harari|year=2007 |publisher=The Boydell Press |pages=53\u201373}}</ref>\n*[[1615]] &ndash; The first [[R\u00e9collet]] [[missionaries]] arrive at [[Quebec City]], from [[Rouen]], France.\n*[[1676]] &ndash; [[Franco-Dutch War]]: [[Kingdom of France|France]] ensured the supremacy of its naval fleet for the remainder of the war with its victory in the [[Battle of Palermo]].\n*[[1692]] &ndash; [[Bridget Bishop]] is the first person to be [[Salem witch trials|tried for witchcraft]] in [[Salem, Massachusetts]]; she was found guilty and later hanged.\n*[[1763]] &ndash; [[Pontiac's Rebellion]]: At what is now [[Mackinaw City, Michigan]], [[Chippewa]]s capture [[Fort Michilimackinac]] by diverting the garrison's attention with a game of [[lacrosse]], then chasing a ball into the fort.\n*[[1774]] &ndash; [[Intolerable Acts]]: The [[Quartering Act]] is enacted, allowing a governor in [[Thirteen Colonies|colonial America]] to house British soldiers in uninhabited houses, outhouses, barns, or other buildings if suitable quarters are not provided.\n*[[1793]] &ndash; [[French Revolution]]: [[Fran\u00e7ois Hanriot]], leader of the Parisian National Guard, arrests 22 [[Girondist]]s selected by [[Jean-Paul Marat]], setting the stage for the [[Reign of Terror]].\n*[[1805]] &ndash; [[Napoleonic Wars]]: A [[First French Empire|Franco]]-[[Enlightenment in Spain|Spanish]] fleet [[Battle of Diamond Rock|recaptures Diamond Rock]], an uninhabited island at the entrance to the bay leading to [[Fort-de-France]], from the British.\n*[[1835]] &ndash; [[P. T. Barnum]] and his circus start their first tour of the United States.\n*[[1848]] &ndash; The [[Prague Slavic Congress, 1848|Slavic congress]] in [[Prague]] begins.\n*[[1866]] &ndash; The [[Fenian Brotherhood|Fenians]] defeat Canadian forces at [[Battle of Ridgeway|Ridgeway]] and [[Battle of Fort Erie (1866)|Fort Erie]], but the raids end soon after.\n*[[1896]] &ndash; [[Guglielmo Marconi]] applies for a [[patent]] for his [[Wireless telegraphy|wireless telegraph]].\n*[[1909]] &ndash; [[Alfred Deakin]] becomes [[Prime Minister of Australia]] for the third time.\n*[[1910]] &ndash; [[Charles Rolls]], a co-founder of [[Rolls-Royce Limited]], becomes the first man to make a non-stop double crossing of the [[English Channel]] by plane.\n*[[1919]] &ndash; [[Anarchism|Anarchists]] simultaneously [[1919 United States anarchist bombings|set off bombs]] in eight separate U.S. cities.\n*[[1924]] &ndash; U.S. President [[Calvin Coolidge]] signs the [[Indian Citizenship Act]] into law, granting [[citizenship]] to all [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]] born within the territorial limits of the United States.\n*[[1941]] &ndash; [[World War II]]: German [[Fallschirmj\u00e4ger (World War II)|paratroopers]] murder Greek civilians in the villages of [[Massacre of Kondomari|Kondomari]] and [[Alikianos executions|Alikianos]].\n*[[1946]] &ndash; [[Italian constitutional referendum, 1946|Birth of the Italian Republic]]: In a [[referendum]], [[Italy|Italians]] vote to turn Italy from a [[monarchy]] into a [[Republic]]. After the referendum, King [[Umberto II of Italy]] is exiled.\n*[[1953]] &ndash; The [[coronation of Queen Elizabeth II]], who is crowned Queen of the [[United Kingdom]], [[Canada]], [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]] and Her Other Realms and Territories & [[Head of the Commonwealth]], the first major international event to be televised.\n*[[1955]] &ndash; The [[Soviet Union|USSR]] and [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]] sign the [[Belgrade declaration]] and thus normalize relations between both countries, discontinued since [[1948]].\n*[[1962]] &ndash; During the [[1962 FIFA World Cup]], police had to intervene multiple times in fights between [[Chile national football team|Chilean]] and [[Italy national football team|Italian]] players in [[Battle of Santiago (1962 FIFA World Cup)|one of the most violent games]] in [[association football|football]] history.\n*[[1964]] &ndash; The [[Palestine Liberation Organization]] (PLO) is formed.<ref>[http://avalon.law.yale.edu/20th_century/plocov.asp ''The Palestinian National Charter: Resolutions of the Palestine National Council July 1-17, 1968''], on Avalon</ref>\n*[[1966]] &ndash; [[Surveyor program]]: ''[[Surveyor 1]]'' lands in [[Oceanus Procellarum]] on the [[Moon]], becoming the first U.S. [[spacecraft]] to soft-land on another world.\n*[[1967]] &ndash; [[Luis Monge (mass murderer)|Luis Monge]] is executed in [[capital punishment in Colorado|Colorado]]'s [[gas chamber]], in the last [[Furman v. Georgia|pre-''Furman'']] execution in the United States.\n*  1967   &ndash; Protests in [[West Berlin]] against the arrival of the [[Shah]] of [[Iran]] turn into riots, during which [[Benno Ohnesorg]] is killed by a police officer. His death results in the founding of the [[terrorism|terrorist]] group [[Movement 2 June]].\n*[[1979]] &ndash; [[Pope John Paul II]] starts his first official visit to his native Poland, becoming the first [[Pope]] to visit a [[Communist]] country.\n*[[1983]] &ndash; After an emergency landing because of an in-flight fire, twenty-three passengers aboard [[Air Canada Flight 797]] are killed when a [[flashover]] occurs as the plane's doors open. Because of this incident, numerous new safety regulations are put in place.\n*[[1990]] &ndash; The [[June 1990 Lower Ohio Valley tornado outbreak|Lower Ohio Valley tornado outbreak]] spawns 66 confirmed tornadoes in [[Illinois]], [[Indiana]], [[Kentucky]], and [[Ohio]], killing 12. \n*[[1997]] &ndash; In [[Denver]], [[Timothy McVeigh]] is convicted on 15 counts of murder and [[conspiracy (criminal)|conspiracy]] for his role in the [[1995]] [[Oklahoma City bombing|bombing]] of the [[Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building]] in [[Oklahoma City]], in which 168 people died. He was executed four years later.\n*[[2003]] &ndash; Europe launches its first voyage to another planet, [[Mars]]. The [[European Space Agency]]'s ''[[Mars Express]]'' probe launches from the [[Baikonur]] space center in [[Kazakhstan]].\n*[[2012]] &ndash; Former [[Egyptian President]] [[Hosni Mubarak]] is sentenced to [[life imprisonment]] for his role in the killing of demonstrators during the [[2011 Egyptian revolution]].\n*[[2014]] &ndash; [[Telangana]] officially [[Andhra Pradesh Reorganisation Act, 2014|becomes]] the 29th [[States of India|state of India]], formed from ten districts of northwestern [[Andhra Pradesh]].\n<!-- PLEASE do not add video game, movie, or album release dates. They will be removed on sight -->\n\n==Births==\n*[[1305]] &ndash; [[Abu Sa'id Bahadur Khan]], ruler of Ilkhanate (d. 1335) \n*[[1423]] &ndash; [[Ferdinand I of Naples]] (d. 1494) \n*[[1489]] &ndash; [[Charles, Duke of Vend\u00f4me]] (d. 1537)<ref>{{cite book|author=Great Britain. Public Record Office|title=Calendar of Letters, Despatches, and State Papers Relating to the Negotiations Between England and Spain|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ies_AAAAYAAJ|year=1969|publisher=Longman, Green, Longman, & Roberts|page=567}}</ref> \n*[[1535]] &ndash; [[Pope Leo XI]] (d. 1605)<ref>{{cite book|author=Michael J. Walsh|title=Lives of the Popes: Illustrated Biographies of Every Pope from St. Peter to the Present|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GnwsAQAAMAAJ|year=1998|publisher=Salamander|isbn=978-0-86101-960-1|page=213}}</ref>\n*[[1602]] &ndash; [[Rudolf Christian, Count of East Frisia]], Ruler of East Frisia (d. 1628)\n*[[1621]] &ndash; [[Rutger von Ascheberg]], Courland-born soldier in Swedish service (d. 1693)<ref>{{cite book|author=Gustaf Bondeson|title=G\u00f6teborg today and yesterday|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1xZpAAAAMAAJ|year=1971|publisher=Wez\u00e4ta F\u00f6rlag|page=18}}</ref>\n*  1621   &ndash; (baptized) [[Isaac van Ostade]], Dutch painter (d. 1649)<ref>{{cite book|author=Herwig Guratzsch|title=Dutch and Flemish Painting|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HrvqAAAAMAAJ|date=1 January 1981|publisher=Vilo|isbn=978-0-86710-003-7|page=281}}</ref>\n*[[1638]] &ndash; [[Henry Hyde, 2nd Earl of Clarendon]] (d. 1709)\n*[[1644]] &ndash; [[William Salmon]], English medical writer (d. 1713)\n*[[1739]] &ndash; [[Jabez Bowen]], American colonel and politician, 45th [[Deputy Governor of Rhode Island]] (d. 1815)\n*[[1740]] &ndash; [[Marquis de Sade]], French philosopher and politician (d. 1814)\n*[[1743]] &ndash; [[Alessandro Cagliostro]], Italian occultist and explorer (d. 1795)\n*[[1773]] &ndash; [[John Randolph of Roanoke]], American planter and politician, 8th [[United States Ambassador to Russia]] (d. 1833)\n*[[1774]] &ndash; [[William Lawson (explorer)|William Lawson]], English-Australian explorer and politician (d. 1850)\n*[[1813]] &ndash; [[Daniel Pollen]], Irish-New Zealand politician, 9th [[Prime Minister of New Zealand]] (d. 1896)\n*[[1823]] &ndash; [[G\u00e9d\u00e9on Ouimet]], Canadian lawyer and politician, 2nd [[Premier of Quebec]] (d. 1905)\n*[[1835]] &ndash; [[Pope Pius X]] (d. 1914)\n*[[1838]] &ndash; [[Duchess Alexandra Petrovna of Oldenburg]] (d. 1900)\n*[[1840]] &ndash; [[Thomas Hardy]], English novelist and poet (d. 1928)\n*  1840   &ndash; [[\u00c9mile Munier]], French artist (d. 1895)\n*[[1857]] &ndash; [[Edward Elgar]], English composer and educator (d. 1934)\n*  1857   &ndash; [[Karl Adolph Gjellerup]], Danish author and poet, [[Nobel Prize in Literature|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 1919)\n*[[1861]] &ndash; [[Concordia Selander]], Swedish actress and manager (d. 1935)\n*[[1863]] &ndash; [[Felix Weingartner]], Croatian-Austrian pianist, composer, and conductor (d. 1942)\n*[[1865]] &ndash; [[George Lohmann]], English cricketer (d. 1901)\n*  1865   &ndash; [[Adelaide Casely-Hayford]], [[Sierra Leone Creole people|Sierra Leone Creole]] [[advocate]] and activist for cultural [[nationalism]] (d. 1960)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/women/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/casely-hayford-adelaide-1868-1960|title=Casely-Hayford, Adelaide (1868\u20131960) - Dictionary definition of Casely-Hayford, Adelaide (1868\u20131960) {{!}} Encyclopedia.com: FREE online dictionary|website=www.encyclopedia.com|language=en|access-date=2018-02-08}}</ref>\n*[[1869]] &ndash; [[Jack O'Connor (catcher)|Jack O'Connor]], American baseball player and manager (d. 1937)\n*[[1875]] &ndash; [[Charles Stewart Mott]], American businessman and politician, 50th [[List of mayors of Flint, Michigan|Mayor of Flint, Michigan]] (d. 1973)\n*[[1878]] &ndash; [[Wallace Hartley]], English violinist and bandleader (d. 1912)\n*[[1881]] &ndash; [[Walter Egan (golfer)|Walter Egan]], American golfer (d. 1971)\n*[[1891]] &ndash; [[Thurman Arnold]], American lawyer and judge (d. 1969)\n*  1891   &ndash; [[Takijir\u014d \u014cnishi]], Japanese admiral and pilot (d. 1945)\n*[[1899]] &ndash; [[Lotte Reiniger]], German animator and director (d. 1981)\n*  1899   &ndash; [[Edwin Way Teale]], American environmentalist and photographer (d. 1980)\n*[[1904]] &ndash; [[Frank Runacres]], English painter and educator (d. 1974)\n*  1904   &ndash; [[Johnny Weissmuller]], Hungarian-American swimmer and actor (d. 1984)\n*[[1907]] &ndash; [[Dorothy West]], American journalist and author (d. 1998)\n*  1907   &ndash; [[John Lehmann]], English poet and publisher (d. 1987)\n*[[1910]] &ndash; [[Hector Dyer]], American sprinter (d. 1990)\n*[[1911]] &ndash; [[Joe McCluskey]], American runner (d. 2002)\n*[[1913]] &ndash; [[Barbara Pym]], English author (d. 1980)\n*  1913   &ndash; [[Elsie Tu]], English-Hong Kong educator and politician (d. 2015)\n*[[1914]] &ndash; [[Johnny Bulla]], American golfer (d. 2003)\n*[[1915]] &ndash; [[Alexandru Nicolschi]], Romanian spy (d. 1992)\n*[[1917]] &ndash; [[Heinz Sielmann]], German photographer and director (d. 2006)\n*[[1918]] &ndash; [[Ruth Atkinson]], Canadian-American illustrator (d. 1997)\n*  1918   &ndash; [[Kathryn Tucker Windham]], American journalist and author (d. 2011)\n*[[1919]] &ndash; [[Nat Mayer Shapiro]], American painter (d. 2005)\n*[[1920]] &ndash; [[Frank G. Clement]], American lawyer and politician, 41st [[Governor of Tennessee]] (d. 1969)\n*  1920   &ndash; [[Yolande Donlan]], American-English actress (d. 2014)\n*  1920   &ndash; [[Marcel Reich-Ranicki]], Polish-German author and critic (d. 2013)\n*  1920   &ndash; [[Tex Schramm]], American businessman (d. 2003)\n*  1920   &ndash; [[Johnny Speight]], English screenwriter and producer (d. 1998)\n*[[1921]] &ndash; [[Betty Freeman]], American photographer and philanthropist (d. 2009)\n*  1921   &ndash; [[Ernie Royal]], American trumpet player (d. 1983)\n*  1921   &ndash; [[Sigmund Sternberg]], Hungarian-English businessman and philanthropist (d. 2016)\n*  1921   &ndash; [[Andr\u00e1s Szennay]], Hungarian priest (d. 2012)\n*[[1922]] &ndash; [[Juan Antonio Bardem]], Spanish director and screenwriter (d. 2002)\n*  1922   &ndash; [[Carmen Silvera]], Canadian-English actress (d. 2002)\n*[[1923]] &ndash; [[Lloyd Shapley]], American mathematician and economist, [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 2016)\n*[[1924]] &ndash; [[June Callwood]], Canadian journalist, author, and activist (d. 2007)\n*[[1926]] &ndash; [[Chiyonoyama Masanobu]], Japanese sumo wrestler, the 41st [[Makuuchi#Yokozuna|Yokozuna]] (d. 1977)\n*  1926   &ndash; [[Milo O'Shea]], Irish-American actor (d. 2013)\n*[[1927]] &ndash; [[W. Watts Biggers]], American author, screenwriter, and animator (d. 2013)\n*  1927   &ndash; [[Christopher Slade]], English lawyer and judge\n*[[1928]] &ndash; [[Erzsi Kov\u00e1cs]], Hungarian singer (d. 2014)\n*  1928   &ndash; [[Rafael A. Lecuona]], Cuban-American gymnast and academic (d. 2014)\n*[[1929]] &ndash; [[Norton Juster]], American architect, author, and academic\n*  1929   &ndash; [[Ken McGregor]], Australian tennis player (d. 2007)\n*[[1930]] &ndash; [[Pete Conrad]], American captain, pilot, and astronaut (d. 1999)\n*[[1933]] &ndash; [[Jerry Lumpe]], American baseball player and coach (d. 2014)\n* 1933 &ndash; [[Pete Robinson (drag racer)|Lew \"Sneaky Pete\" Robinson]], [[Drag racing|drag racer]] (d. 1971)<ref>[http://www.motorsportmemorial.org/focus.php?db=ct&n=1147 Motorsportmemorial.org] (retrieved 4 October 2018)</ref>\n*[[1934]] &ndash; [[Johnny Carter (singer)|Johnny Carter]], American singer (d. 2009)\n*[[1935]] &ndash; [[Carol Shields]], American-Canadian novelist and short story writer (d. 2003)\n*  1935   &ndash; [[Dimitri Kitsikis]], Greek poet and educator\n*[[1936]] &ndash; [[Volodymyr Holubnychy]], Ukrainian race walker\n*[[1937]] &ndash; [[Rosalyn Higgins]], English lawyer and judge\n*  1937   &ndash; [[Sally Kellerman]], American actress \n*  1937   &ndash; [[Jimmy Jones (singer)|Jimmy Jones]], American singer-songwriter (d. 2012)\n*  1937   &ndash; [[Robert Paul]], Canadian figure skater and choreographer\n*  1937   &ndash; [[Deric Washburn]], American screenwriter and playwright\n*[[1938]] &ndash; [[Kevin Brownlow]], English historian and author\n*  1938   &ndash; [[George William Penrose, Lord Penrose]], Scottish lawyer and judge\n*[[1939]] &ndash; [[Charles Miller (musician)|Charles Miller]], American musician (d. 1980)\n*  1939   &ndash; [[John Schlee]], American golfer (d. 2000)\n*[[1940]] &ndash; [[Constantine II of Greece]]\n*[[1941]] &ndash; [[\u00dcnal Aysal]], Turkish businessman\n*  1941   &ndash; [[Stacy Keach]], American actor \n*  1941   &ndash; [[Lou Nanne]], Canadian-American ice hockey player and manager\n*  1941   &ndash; [[Charlie Watts]], English drummer, songwriter, and producer \n*[[1942]] &ndash; [[Mike Ahern (Australian politician)|Mike Ahern]], Australian politician, 32nd [[Premier of Queensland]]\n*[[1943]] &ndash; [[Charles Haid]], American actor and director\n*  1943   &ndash; [[Crescenzio Sepe]], Italian cardinal \n*[[1944]] &ndash; [[Robert Elliott (actor born 1944)|Robert Elliott]], American actor (d. 2004)\n*  1944   &ndash; [[Marvin Hamlisch]], American composer and conductor (d. 2012)\n*[[1945]] &ndash; [[Richard Long (artist)|Richard Long]], English painter, sculptor, and photographer\n*  1945   &ndash; [[Bonnie Newman]], American businessman and politician\n*[[1946]] &ndash; [[Lasse Hallstr\u00f6m]], Swedish director, producer, and screenwriter\n*  1946   &ndash; [[Peter Sutcliffe]], UK serial killer\n*[[1948]] &ndash; [[Jerry Mathers]], American actor\n*[[1949]] &ndash; [[Heather Couper]], English astronomer and physicist\n*  1949   &ndash; [[Frank Rich]], American journalist and critic\n*[[1950]] &ndash; [[Jonathan Evans (politician)|Jonathan Evans]], Welsh lawyer and politician\n*  1950   &ndash; [[Joanna Gleason]], Canadian actress and singer\n*  1950   &ndash; [[Anne Phillips]], English theorist and academic\n*  1950   &ndash; [[Mom\u010dilo Vukoti\u0107]], Serbian footballer and manager\n*[[1951]] &ndash; [[Gilbert Baker (artist)|Gilbert Baker]], American artist, gay rights activist, and designer of the rainbow flag (d. 2017)\n*  1951   &ndash; [[Arnold M\u00fchren]], Dutch footballer and manager\n*  1951   &ndash; [[Larry Robinson]], Canadian ice hockey player and coach\n*  1951   &ndash; [[Alexander Wylie, Lord Kinclaven]], Scottish lawyer, judge, and educator\n*[[1952]] &ndash; [[Gary Bettman]], American commissioner of the National Hockey League \n*[[1953]] &ndash; [[Vidar Johansen (musician)|Vidar Johansen]], Norwegian saxophonist\n*  1953   &ndash; [[Craig Stadler]], American golfer\n*  1953   &ndash; [[Cornel West]], American philosopher, author, and academic\n*[[1954]] &ndash; [[Dennis Haysbert]], American actor and producer\n*[[1955]] &ndash; [[Dana Carvey]], American comedian and actor \n*  1955   &ndash; [[Nandan Nilekani]], Indian businessman, co-founded [[Infosys]] \n*  1955   &ndash; [[Mani Ratnam]], Indian director, producer, and screenwriter\n*  1955   &ndash; [[Michael Steele (musician)|Michael Steele]], American singer-songwriter and bass player\n*[[1956]] &ndash; [[Jan Lammers]], Dutch race car driver\n*[[1957]] &ndash; [[Mark Lawrenson]], English footballer and manager\n*[[1958]] &ndash; [[Lex Luger]], American wrestler and football player \n*[[1959]] &ndash; [[Rineke Dijkstra]], Dutch photographer\n*  1959   &ndash; [[Lydia Lunch]], American singer-songwriter, guitarist, and actress\n*  1959   &ndash; [[Erwin Olaf]], Dutch photographer\n*[[1960]] &ndash; [[Olga Bondarenko]], Russian runner\n*  1960   &ndash; [[Tony Hadley]], English singer-songwriter and actor \n*  1960   &ndash; [[Kyle Petty]], American race car driver and sportscaster\n*[[1961]] &ndash; [[Dez Cadena]], American singer-songwriter and guitarist \n*[[1962]] &ndash; [[Mark Plaatjes]], South African-American runner and coach\n*[[1963]] &ndash; [[Anand Abhyankar]], Indian actor (d. 2012)\n*[[1964]] &ndash; [[Caroline Link]], German director and screenwriter\n*[[1965]] &ndash; [[Russ Courtnall]], Canadian ice hockey player\n*  1965   &ndash; [[Mark Waugh]], Australian cricketer and journalist\n*  1965   &ndash; [[Steve Waugh]], Australian cricketer\n*[[1966]] &ndash; [[Dayana Cadeau]], Haitian born Canadian-American professional bodybuilder<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120711115048/http://www.dayana-cadeau.com:80/about.html|title=The Official Home Page|date=2012-07-11|access-date=2018-05-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120706094348/http://interviews.fbbfan.com/2009/march/dayanacadeau.html|title=FBBFan.com Interview of the Month: March 2009 Dayana Cadeau|date=2012-07-06|access-date=2018-05-23}}</ref>\n*1966 &ndash; [[Candace Gingrich]], American activist<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.debtaylor.com/fha/gingrichbio.html|title=Bio on Candace Gingrich|last=Taylor|first=Deb|website=www.debtaylor.com|access-date=2018-03-12}}</ref>\n*1966 &ndash; [[Pedro Guerra]], Spanish singer-songwriter\n*  1966   &ndash; [[Petra van Staveren]], Dutch swimmer\n*[[1967]] &ndash; [[Remigija Nazarovien\u0117]], Lithuanian heptathlete and coach\n*  1967   &ndash; [[Mike Stanton (left-handed pitcher)|Mike Stanton]], American baseball player\n*[[1968]] &ndash; [[Merril Bainbridge]], Australian singer-songwriter\n*  1968   &ndash; [[Andy Cohen (television personality)|Andy Cohen]], American television host\n*[[1969]] &ndash; [[Kurt Abbott]], American baseball player\n*  1969   &ndash; [[Paulo S\u00e9rgio (footballer, born 1969)|Paulo S\u00e9rgio]], Brazilian footballer\n*  1969   &ndash; [[David Wheaton]], American tennis player, radio host, and author\n*[[1970]] &ndash; [[B Real]], American rapper and actor\n*[[1971]] &ndash; [[Kate\u0159ina Jacques]], Czech translator and politician\n*[[1972]] &ndash; [[Wayne Brady]], American actor, comedian, game show host, and singer\n*  1972   &ndash; [[Ra\u00fal Iba\u00f1ez]], American baseball player\n*  1972   &ndash; [[Wentworth Miller]], American actor and screenwriter\n*[[1973]] &ndash; [[Marko Kristal]], Estonian footballer and manager\n*  1973   &ndash; [[Neifi P