rican biologist and academic, [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry|Nobel Prize]] laureate (b. 1926)\n* [[2017]] &ndash; [[Peter Sallis]], English actor (b. 1921)\n<!--Do not add people without Wikipedia articles to this list. Do not trust \"this year in history\" websites for accurate date information. Do not link multiple occurrences of the same year, just link the first occurrence.-->\n\n==Holidays and observances==\n* [[Children's Day]] ([[North Korea]])\n* Christian [[feast day]]:\n** [[Alexander (martyr)]]\n** [[Erasmus of Formia|Elmo]]\n** [[Felix of Nicosia]]\n** [[Marcellinus and Peter]]\n** [[Martyrs of Lyon]], including [[Blandina]]\n** [[Pope Eugene I]]\n** [[Saint Pothinus|Pothinus]]\n** [[June 2 (Eastern Orthodox liturgics)]]\n* [[Civil Aviation Day]] ([[Azerbaijan]])\n* [[Public_holidays_in_Bhutan#Coronation_of_King_Jigme_Singye_Wangchuck|Coronation of King Jigme Singye Wangchuck]], also Social Forestry Day ([[Bhutan]])\n* [[Day of Hristo Botev]] ([[Bulgaria]])\n* [[Decoration Day (Canada)]]\n* [[Festa della Repubblica]] ([[Italy]])\n* [[International Sex Workers Day]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/june/2 BBC: On This Day]\n* {{NYT On this day|month=06|day=02}}\n* [http://canadachannel.ca/todayincanadianhistory/index.php/June_2 Today in Canadian History]\n\n{{months}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:June 02}}\n[[Category:Days of the year]]\n[[Category:June]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}{{calendar}}\n{{This date in recent years}}\n{{Day}}\n\n==Events==\n* [[455]] &ndash; [[Sack of Rome (455)|Sack of Rome]]: [[Vandals]] enter Rome, and plunder the city for two weeks.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/cambridgemediev00whitgoog |title=The Cambridge Medieval History |last=Gwatkin |first=Henry Melvill |last2=Whitney |first2=James Pounder |last3=Tanner |first3=Joseph Robson |last4=Previt\u00e9-Orton |first4=Charles William |last5=Brooke |first5=Zachary Nugent |publisher=Macmillan |year=1911 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/cambridgemediev00whitgoog/page/n366 308] |display-authors=2 |quote=On 2 June Gaiseric marched into Rome ... The Vandals stayed a fortnight...}}</ref>\n*[[1098]] &ndash; [[First Crusade]]: The first [[Siege of Antioch]] ends as Crusader forces take the city; the second siege began five days later.<ref>{{cite book |chapter=The Gateway to the Middle East: Antioch, 1098 |title=Special Operations in the Age of Chivalry, 1100\u20131550 |first=Yuval Noah |last=Harari| authorlink=Yuval Noah Harari|year=2007 |publisher=The Boydell Press |pages=53\u201373}}</ref>\n*[[1615]] &ndash; The first [[R\u00e9collet]] [[missionaries]] arrive at [[Quebec City]], from [[Rouen]], France.\n*[[1676]] &ndash; [[Franco-Dutch War]]: [[Kingdom of France|France]] ensured the supremacy of its naval fleet for the remainder of the war with its victory in the [[Battle of Palermo]].\n*[[1692]] &ndash; [[Bridget Bishop]] is the first person to be [[Salem witch trials|tried for witchcraft]] in [[Salem, Massachusetts]]; she was found guilty and later hanged.\n*[[1763]] &ndash; [[Pontiac's Rebellion]]: At what is now [[Mackinaw City, Michigan]], [[Chippewa]]s capture [[Fort Michilimackinac]] by diverting the garrison's attention with a game of [[lacrosse]], then chasing a ball into the fort.\n*[[1774]] &ndash; [[Intolerable Acts]]: The [[Quartering Act]] is enacted, allowing a governor in [[Thirteen Colonies|colonial America]] to house British soldiers in uninhabited houses, outhouses, barns, or other buildings if suitable quarters are not provided.\n*[[1793]] &ndash; [[French Revolution]]: [[Fran\u00e7ois Hanriot]], leader of the Parisian National Guard, arrests 22 [[Girondist]]s selected by [[Jean-Paul Marat]], setting the stage for the [[Reign of Terror]].\n*[[1805]] &ndash; [[Napoleonic Wars]]: A [[First French Empire|Franco]]-[[Enlightenment in Spain|Spanish]] fleet [[Battle of Diamond Rock|recaptures Diamond Rock]], an uninhabited island at the entrance to the bay leading to [[Fort-de-France]], from the British.\n*[[1835]] &ndash; [[P. T. Barnum]] and his circus start their first tour of the United States.\n*[[1848]] &ndash; The [[Prague Slavic Congress, 1848|Slavic congress]] in [[Prague]] begins.\n*[[1866]] &ndash; The [[Fenian Brotherhood|Fenians]] defeat Canadian forces at [[Battle of Ridgeway|Ridgeway]] and [[Battle of Fort Erie (1866)|Fort Erie]], but the raids end soon after.\n*[[1896]] &ndash; [[Guglielmo Marconi]] applies for a [[patent]] for his [[Wireless telegraphy|wireless telegraph]].\n*[[1909]] &ndash; [[Alfred Deakin]] becomes [[Prime Minister of Australia]] for the third time.\n*[[1910]] &ndash; [[Charles Rolls]], a co-founder of [[Rolls-Royce Limited]], becomes the first man to make a non-stop double crossing of the [[English Channel]] by plane.\n*[[1919]] &ndash; [[Anarchism|Anarchists]] simultaneously [[1919 United States anarchist bombings|set off bombs]] in eight separate U.S. cities.\n*[[1924]] &ndash; U.S. President [[Calvin Coolidge]] signs the [[Indian Citizenship Act]] into law, granting [[citizenship]] to all [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]] born within the territorial limits of the United States.\n*[[1941]] &ndash; [[World War II]]: German [[Fallschirmj\u00e4ger (World War II)|paratroopers]] murder Greek civilians in the villages of [[Massacre of Kondomari|Kondomari]] and [[Alikianos executions|Alikianos]].\n*[[1946]] &ndash; [[Italian constitutional referendum, 1946|Birth of the Italian Republic]]: In a [[referendum]], [[Italy|Italians]] vote to turn Italy from a [[monarchy]] into a [[Republic]]. After the referendum, King [[Umberto II of Italy]] is exiled.\n*[[1953]] &ndash; The [[coronation of Queen Elizabeth II]], who is crowned Queen of the [[United Kingdom]], [[Canada]], [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]] and Her Other Realms and Territories & [[Head of the Commonwealth]], the first major international event to be televised.\n*[[1955]] &ndash; The [[Soviet Union|USSR]] and [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]] sign the [[Belgrade declaration]] and thus normalize relations between both countries, discontinued since [[1948]].\n*[[1962]] &ndash; During the [[1962 FIFA World Cup]], police had to intervene multiple times in fights between [[Chile national football team|Chilean]] and [[Italy national football team|Italian]] players in [[Battle of Santiago (1962 FIFA World Cup)|one of the most violent games]] in [[association football|football]] history.\n*[[1964]] &ndash; The [[Palestine Liberation Organization]] (PLO) is formed.<ref>[http://avalon.law.yale.edu/20th_century/plocov.asp ''The Palestinian National Charter: Resolutions of the Palestine National Council July 1-17, 1968''], on Avalon</ref>\n*[[1966]] &ndash; [[Surveyor program]]: ''[[Surveyor 1]]'' lands in [[Oceanus Procellarum]] on the [[Moon]], becoming the first U.S. [[spacecraft]] to soft-land on another world.\n*[[1967]] &ndash; [[Luis Monge (mass murderer)|Luis Monge]] is executed in [[capital punishment in Colorado|Colorado]]'s [[gas chamber]], in the last [[Furman v. Georgia|pre-''Furman'']] execution in the United States.\n*  1967   &ndash; Protests in [[West Berlin]] against the arrival of the [[Shah]] of [[Iran]] turn into riots, during which [[Benno Ohnesorg]] is killed by a police officer. His death results in the founding of the [[terrorism|terrorist]] group [[Movement 2 June]].\n*[[1979]] &ndash; [[Pope John Paul II]] starts his first official visit to his native Poland, becoming the first [[Pope]] to visit a [[Communist]] country.\n*[[1983]] &ndash; After an emergency landing because of an in-flight fire, twenty-three passengers aboard [[Air Canada Flight 797]] are killed when a [[flashover]] occurs as the plane's doors open. Because of this incident, numerous new safety regulations are put in place.\n*[[1990]] &ndash; The [[June 1990 Lower Ohio Valley tornado outbreak|Lower Ohio Valley tornado outbreak]] spawns 66 confirmed tornadoes in [[Illinois]], [[Indiana]], [[Kentucky]], and [[Ohio]], killing 12. \n*[[1997]] &ndash; In [[Denver]], [[Timothy McVeigh]] is convicted on 15 counts of murder and [[conspiracy (criminal)|conspiracy]] for his role in the [[1995]] [[Oklahoma City bombing|bombing]] of the [[Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building]] in [[Oklahoma City]], in which 168 people died. He was executed four years later.\n*[[2003]] &ndash; Europe launches its first voyage to another planet, [[Mars]]. The [[European Space Agency]]'s ''[[Mars Express]]'' probe launches from the [[Baikonur]] space center in [[Kazakhstan]].\n*[[2012]] &ndash; Former [[Egyptian President]] [[Hosni Mubarak]] is sentenced to [[life imprisonment]] for his role in the killing of demonstrators during the [[2011 Egyptian revolution]].\n*[[2014]] &ndash; [[Telangana]] officially [[Andhra Pradesh Reorganisation Act, 2014|becomes]] the 29th [[States of India|state of India]], formed from ten districts of northwestern [[Andhra Pradesh]].\n<!-- PLEASE do not add video game, movie, or album release dates. They will be removed on sight -->\n\n==Births==\n*[[1305]] &ndash; [[Abu Sa'id Bahadur Khan]], ruler of Ilkhanate (d. 1335) \n*[[1423]] &ndash; [[Ferdinand I of Naples]] (d. 1494) \n*[[1489]] &ndash; [[Charles, Duke of Vend\u00f4me]] (d. 1537)<ref>{{cite book|author=Great Britain. Public Record Office|title=Calendar of Letters, Despatches, and State Papers Relating to the Negotiations Between England and Spain|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ies_AAAAYAAJ|year=1969|publisher=Longman, Green, Longman, & Roberts|page=567}}</ref> \n*[[1535]] &ndash; [[Pope Leo XI]] (d. 1605)<ref>{{cite book|author=Michael J. Walsh|title=Lives of the Popes: Illustrated Biographies of Every Pope from St. Peter to the Present|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GnwsAQAAMAAJ|year=1998|publisher=Salamander|isbn=978-0-86101-960-1|page=213}}</ref>\n*[[1602]] &ndash; [[Rudolf Christian, Count of East Frisia]], Ruler of East Frisia (d. 1628)\n*[[1621]] &ndash; [[Rutger von Ascheberg]], Courland-born soldier in Swedish service (d. 1693)<ref>{{cite book|author=Gustaf Bondeson|title=G\u00f6teborg today and yesterday|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1xZpAAAAMAAJ|year=1971|publisher=Wez\u00e4ta F\u00f6rlag|page=18}}</ref>\n*  1621   &ndash; (baptized) [[Isaac van Ostade]], Dutch painter (d. 1649)<ref>{{cite book|author=Herwig Guratzsch|title=Dutch and Flemish Painting|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HrvqAAAAMAAJ|date=1 January 1981|publisher=Vilo|isbn=978-0-86710-003-7|page=281}}</ref>\n*[[1638]] &ndash; [[Henry Hyde, 2nd Earl of Clarendon]] (d. 1709)\n*[[1644]] &ndash; [[William Salmon]], English medical writer (d. 1713)\n*[[1739]] &ndash; [[Jabez Bowen]], American colonel and politician, 45th [[Deputy Governor of Rhode Island]] (d. 1815)\n*[[1740]] &ndash; [[Marquis de Sade]], French philosopher and politician (d. 1814)\n*[[1743]] &ndash; [[Alessandro Cagliostro]], Italian occultist and explorer (d. 1795)\n*[[1773]] &ndash; [[John Randolph of Roanoke]], American planter and politician, 8th [[United States Ambassador to Russia]] (d. 1833)\n*[[1774]] &ndash; [[William Lawson (explorer)|William Lawson]], English-Australian explorer and politician (d. 1850)\n*[[1813]] &ndash; [[Daniel Pollen]], Irish-New Zealand politician, 9th [[Prime Minister of New Zealand]] (d. 1896)\n*[[1823]] &ndash; [[G\u00e9d\u00e9on Ouimet]], Canadian lawyer and politician, 2nd [[Premier of Quebec]] (d. 1905)\n*[[1835]] &ndash; [[Pope Pius X]] (d. 1914)\n*[[1838]] &ndash; [[Duchess Alexandra Petrovna of Oldenburg]] (d. 1900)\n*[[1840]] &ndash; [[Thomas Hardy]], English novelist and poet (d. 1928)\n*  1840   &ndash; [[\u00c9mile Munier]], French artist (d. 1895)\n*[[1857]] &ndash; [[Edward Elgar]], English composer and educator (d. 1934)\n*  1857   &ndash; [[Karl Adolph Gjellerup]], Danish author and poet, [[Nobel Prize in Literature|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 1919)\n*[[1861]] &ndash; [[Concordia Selander]], Swedish actress and manager (d. 1935)\n*[[1863]] &ndash; [[Felix Weingartner]], Croatian-Austrian pianist, composer, and conductor (d. 1942)\n*[[1865]] &ndash; [[George Lohmann]], English cricketer (d. 1901)\n*[[1865]] &ndash; [[Adelaide Casely-Hayford]], [[Sierra Leone Creole people|Sierra Leone Creole]] [[advocate]] and activist for cultural [[nationalism]] (d. 1960)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/women/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/casely-hayford-adelaide-1868-1960|title=Casely-Hayford, Adelaide (1868\u20131960) - Dictionary definition of Casely-Hayford, Adelaide (1868\u20131960) {{!}} Encyclopedia.com: FREE online dictionary|website=www.encyclopedia.com|language=en|access-date=2018-02-08}}</ref>\n*[[1869]] &ndash; [[Jack O'Connor (catcher)|Jack O'Connor]], American baseball player and manager (d. 1937)\n*[[1875]] &ndash; [[Charles Stewart Mott]], American businessman and politician, 50th [[List of mayors of Flint, Michigan|Mayor of Flint, Michigan]] (d. 1973)\n*[[1878]] &ndash; [[Wallace Hartley]], English violinist and bandleader (d. 1912)\n*[[1881]] &ndash; [[Walter Egan (golfer)|Walter Egan]], American golfer (d. 1971)\n*[[1891]] &ndash; [[Thurman Arnold]], American lawyer and judge (d. 1969)\n*  1891   &ndash; [[Takijir\u014d \u014cnishi]], Japanese admiral and pilot (d. 1945)\n*[[1899]] &ndash; [[Lotte Reiniger]], German animator and director (d. 1981)\n*  1899   &ndash; [[Edwin Way Teale]], American environmentalist and photographer (d. 1980)\n*[[1904]] &ndash; [[Frank Runacres]], English painter and educator (d. 1974)\n*  1904   &ndash; [[Johnny Weissmuller]], Hungarian-American swimmer and actor (d. 1984)\n*[[1907]] &ndash; [[Dorothy West]], American journalist and author (d. 1998)\n*  1907   &ndash; [[John Lehmann]], English poet and publisher (d. 1987)\n*[[1910]] &ndash; [[Hector Dyer]], American sprinter (d. 1990)\n*[[1911]] &ndash; [[Joe McCluskey]], American runner (d. 2002)\n*[[1913]] &ndash; [[Barbara Pym]], English author (d. 1980)\n*  1913   &ndash; [[Elsie Tu]], English-Hong Kong educator and politician (d. 2015)\n*[[1914]] &ndash; [[Johnny Bulla]], American golfer (d. 2003)\n*[[1915]] &ndash; [[Alexandru Nicolschi]], Romanian spy (d. 1992)\n*[[1917]] &ndash; [[Heinz Sielmann]], German photographer and director (d. 2006)\n*[[1918]] &ndash; [[Ruth Atkinson]], Canadian-American illustrator (d. 1997)\n*  1918   &ndash; [[Kathryn Tucker Windham]], American journalist and author (d. 2011)\n*[[1919]] &ndash; [[Nat Mayer Shapiro]], American painter (d. 2005)\n*[[1920]] &ndash; [[Frank G. Clement]], American lawyer and politician, 41st [[Governor of Tennessee]] (d. 1969)\n*  1920   &ndash; [[Yolande Donlan]], American-English actress (d. 2014)\n*  1920   &ndash; [[Marcel Reich-Ranicki]], Polish-German author and critic (d. 2013)\n*  1920   &ndash; [[Tex Schramm]], American businessman (d. 2003)\n*  1920   &ndash; [[Johnny Speight]], English screenwriter and producer (d. 1998)\n*[[1921]] &ndash; [[Betty Freeman]], American photographer and philanthropist (d. 2009)\n*  1921   &ndash; [[Ernie Royal]], American trumpet player (d. 1983)\n*  1921   &ndash; [[Sigmund Sternberg]], Hungarian-English businessman and philanthropist (d. 2016)\n*  1921   &ndash; [[Andr\u00e1s Szennay]], Hungarian priest (d. 2012)\n*[[1922]] &ndash; [[Juan Antonio Bardem]], Spanish director and screenwriter (d. 2002)\n*  1922   &ndash; [[Carmen Silvera]], Canadian-English actress (d. 2002)\n*[[1923]] &ndash; [[Lloyd Shapley]], American mathematician and economist, [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 2016)\n*[[1924]] &ndash; [[June Callwood]], Canadian journalist, author, and activist (d. 2007)\n*[[1926]] &ndash; [[Chiyonoyama Masanobu]], Japanese sumo wrestler, the 41st [[Makuuchi#Yokozuna|Yokozuna]] (d. 1977)\n*  1926   &ndash; [[Milo O'Shea]], Irish-American actor (d. 2013)\n*[[1927]] &ndash; [[W. Watts Biggers]], American author, screenwriter, and animator (d. 2013)\n*  1927   &ndash; [[Christopher Slade]], English lawyer and judge\n*[[1928]] &ndash; [[Erzsi Kov\u00e1cs]], Hungarian singer (d. 2014)\n*  1928   &ndash; [[Rafael A. Lecuona]], Cuban-American gymnast and academic (d. 2014)\n*[[1929]] &ndash; [[Norton Juster]], American architect, author, and academic\n*  1929   &ndash; [[Ken McGregor]], Australian tennis player (d. 2007)\n*[[1930]] &ndash; [[Pete Conrad]], American captain, pilot, and astronaut (d. 1999)\n*[[1933]] &ndash; [[Jerry Lumpe]], American baseball player and coach (d. 2014)\n* 1933 &ndash; [[Pete Robinson (drag racer)|Lew \"Sneaky Pete\" Robinson]], [[Drag racing|drag racer]] (d. 1971)<ref>[http://www.motorsportmemorial.org/focus.php?db=ct&n=1147 Motorsportmemorial.org] (retrieved 4 October 2018)</ref>\n*[[1934]] &ndash; [[Johnny Carter (singer)|Johnny Carter]], American singer (d. 2009)\n*[[1935]] &ndash; [[Carol Shields]], American-Canadian novelist and short story writer (d. 2003)\n*  1935   &ndash; [[Dimitri Kitsikis]], Greek poet and educator\n*[[1936]] &ndash; [[Volodymyr Holubnychy]], Ukrainian race walker\n*[[1937]] &ndash; [[Rosalyn Higgins]], English lawyer and judge\n*  1937   &ndash; [[Sally Kellerman]], American actress \n*  1937   &ndash; [[Jimmy Jones (singer)|Jimmy Jones]], American singer-songwriter (d. 2012)\n*  1937   &ndash; [[Robert Paul]], Canadian figure skater and choreographer\n*  1937   &ndash; [[Deric Washburn]], American screenwriter and playwright\n*[[1938]] &ndash; [[Kevin Brownlow]], English historian and author\n*  1938   &ndash; [[George William Penrose, Lord Penrose]], Scottish lawyer and judge\n*[[1939]] &ndash; [[Charles Miller (musician)|Charles Miller]], American musician (d. 1980)\n*  1939   &ndash; [[John Schlee]], American golfer (d. 2000)\n*[[1940]] &ndash; [[Constantine II of Greece]]\n*[[1941]] &ndash; [[\u00dcnal Aysal]], Turkish businessman\n*  1941   &ndash; [[Stacy Keach]], American actor \n*  1941   &ndash; [[Lou Nanne]], Canadian-American ice hockey player and manager\n*  1941   &ndash; [[Charlie Watts]], English drummer, songwriter, and producer \n*[[1942]] &ndash; [[Mike Ahern (Australian politician)|Mike Ahern]], Australian politician, 32nd [[Premier of Queensland]]\n*[[1943]] &ndash; [[Charles Haid]], American actor and director\n*  1943   &ndash; [[Crescenzio Sepe]], Italian cardinal \n*[[1944]] &ndash; [[Robert Elliott (actor born 1944)|Robert Elliott]], American actor (d. 2004)\n*  1944   &ndash; [[Marvin Hamlisch]], American composer and conductor (d. 2012)\n*[[1945]] &ndash; [[Richard Long (artist)|Richard Long]], English painter, sculptor, and photographer\n*  1945   &ndash; [[Bonnie Newman]], American businessman and politician\n*[[1946]] &ndash; [[Lasse Hallstr\u00f6m]], Swedish director, producer, and screenwriter\n*[[1946]] &ndash; [[Peter Sutcliffe]], UK serial killer\n*[[1948]] &ndash; [[Jerry Mathers]], American actor\n*[[1949]] &ndash; [[Heather Couper]], English astronomer and physicist\n*  1949   &ndash; [[Frank Rich]], American journalist and critic\n*[[1950]] &ndash; [[Jonathan Evans (politician)|Jonathan Evans]], Welsh lawyer and politician\n*  1950   &ndash; [[Joanna Gleason]], Canadian actress and singer\n*  1950   &ndash; [[Anne Phillips]], English theorist and academic\n*  1950   &ndash; [[Mom\u010dilo Vukoti\u0107]], Serbian footballer and manager\n*[[1951]] &ndash; [[Gilbert Baker (artist)|Gilbert Baker]], American artist, gay rights activist, and designer of the rainbow flag (d. 2017)\n*[[1951]] &ndash; [[Arnold M\u00fchren]], Dutch footballer and manager\n*  1951   &ndash; [[Larry Robinson]], Canadian ice hockey player and coach\n*  1951   &ndash; [[Alexander Wylie, Lord Kinclaven]], Scottish lawyer, judge, and educator\n*[[1952]] &ndash; [[Gary Bettman]], American commissioner of the National Hockey League \n*[[1953]] &ndash; [[Vidar Johansen (musician)|Vidar Johansen]], Norwegian saxophonist\n*  1953   &ndash; [[Craig Stadler]], American golfer\n*  1953   &ndash; [[Cornel West]], American philosopher, author, and academic\n*[[1954]] &ndash; [[Dennis Haysbert]], American actor and producer\n*[[1955]] &ndash; [[Dana Carvey]], American comedian and actor \n*  1955   &ndash; [[Nandan Nilekani]], Indian businessman, co-founded [[Infosys]] \n*  1955   &ndash; [[Mani Ratnam]], Indian director, producer, and screenwriter\n*  1955   &ndash; [[Michael Steele (musician)|Michael Steele]], American singer-songwriter and bass player\n*[[1956]] &ndash; [[Jan Lammers]], Dutch race car driver\n*[[1957]] &ndash; [[Mark Lawrenson]], English footballer and manager\n*[[1958]] &ndash; [[Lex Luger]], American wrestler and football player \n*[[1959]] &ndash; [[Rineke Dijkstra]], Dutch photographer\n*  1959   &ndash; [[Lydia Lunch]], American singer-songwriter, guitarist, and actress\n*  1959   &ndash; [[Erwin Olaf]], Dutch photographer\n*[[1960]] &ndash; [[Olga Bondarenko]], Russian runner\n*  1960   &ndash; [[Tony Hadley]], English singer-songwriter and actor \n*  1960   &ndash; [[Kyle Petty]], American race car driver and sportscaster\n*[[1961]] &ndash; [[Dez Cadena]], American singer-songwriter and guitarist \n*[[1962]] &ndash; [[Mark Plaatjes]], South African-American runner and coach\n*[[1963]] &ndash; [[Anand Abhyankar]], Indian actor (d. 2012)\n*[[1964]] &ndash; [[Caroline Link]], German director and screenwriter\n*[[1965]] &ndash; [[Russ Courtnall]], Canadian ice hockey player\n*  1965   &ndash; [[Mark Waugh]], Australian cricketer and journalist\n*  1965   &ndash; [[Steve Waugh]], Australian cricketer\n*[[1966]] &ndash; [[Dayana Cadeau]], Haitian born Canadian-American professional bodybuilder<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120711115048/http://www.dayana-cadeau.com:80/about.html|title=The Official Home Page|date=2012-07-11|access-date=2018-05-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120706094348/http://interviews.fbbfan.com/2009/march/dayanacadeau.html|title=FBBFan.com Interview of the Month: March 2009 Dayana Cadeau|date=2012-07-06|access-date=2018-05-23}}</ref>\n*1966 &ndash; [[Candace Gingrich]], American activist<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.debtaylor.com/fha/gingrichbio.html|title=Bio on Candace Gingrich|last=Taylor|first=Deb|website=www.debtaylor.com|access-date=2018-03-12}}</ref>\n*1966 &ndash; [[Pedro Guerra]], Spanish singer-songwriter\n*  1966   &ndash; [[Petra van Staveren]], Dutch swimmer\n*[[1967]] &ndash; [[Remigija Nazarovien\u0117]], Lithuanian heptathlete and coach\n*  1967   &ndash; [[Mike Stanton (left-handed pitcher)|Mike Stanton]], American baseball player\n*[[1968]] &ndash; [[Merril Bainbridge]], Australian singer-songwriter\n*  1968   &ndash; [[Andy Cohen (television personality)|Andy Cohen]], American television host\n*[[1969]] &ndash; [[Kurt Abbott]], American baseball player\n*  1969   &ndash; [[Paulo S\u00e9rgio (footballer, born 1969)|Paulo S\u00e9rgio]], Brazilian footballer\n*  1969   &ndash; [[David Wheaton]], American tennis player, radio host, and author\n*[[1970]] &ndash; [[B Real]], American rapper and actor\n*[[1971]] &ndash; [[Kate\u0159ina Jacques]], Czech translator and politician\n*[[1972]] &ndash; [[Wayne Brady]], American actor, comedian, game show host, and singer\n*  1972   &ndash; [[Ra\u00fal Iba\u00f1ez]], American baseball player\n*  1972   &ndash; [[Wentworth Miller]], American actor and screenwriter\n*[[1973]] &ndash; [[Marko Kristal]], Estonian footballer and manager\n*  1973   &ndash; [[Neifi P\u00e9rez]], Dominican-American baseball player\n*[[1974]] &ndash; [[Gata Kamsky]], Russian-American chess player\n*  1974   &ndash; [[Matt Serra]], American mixed martial artist\n*[[1975]] &ndash; [[Salvatore Scibona]], American author\n*[[1976]] &ndash; [[Earl Boykins]], American basketball player\n*  1976   &ndash; [[Martin \u010cech]], Czech ice hockey player (d. 2007)\n*  1976   &ndash; [[Ant\u00f4nio Rodrigo Nogueira]], Brazilian mixed martial artist and boxer\n*  1976   &ndash; [[Tim Rice-Oxley]], English singer-songwriter and keyboard player \n*[[1977]] &ndash; [[Teet Allas]], Estonian footballer\n*  1977   &ndash; [[A.J. Styles]], American wrestler\n*  1977   &ndash; [[Zachary Quinto]], American actor and producer\n*[[1978]] &ndash; [[Dominic Cooper]], English actor\n*  1978   &ndash; [[Nikki Cox]], American actress\n*  1978   &ndash; [[Justin Long]], American actor \n*  1978   &ndash; [[Yi So-yeon]], [[biotechnologist]] and [[astronaut]], the first [[South Korea|Korean]] in space\n*  1978   &ndash; [[Luke Williamson]], Australian rugby league player\n*[[1979]] &ndash; [[Morena Baccarin]], Brazilian-American actress\n*  1979   &ndash; [[Butterfly Boucher]], Australian singer-songwriter, guitarist, and producer\n*  1979   &ndash; [[Natalia Rodr\u00edguez (athlete)|Natalia Rodr\u00edguez]], Spanish runner\n*[[1980]] &ndash; [[Fabrizio Moretti]], Brazilian-American drummer \n*  1980   &ndash; [[Bobby Simmons]], American basketball player\n*  1980   &ndash; [[Richard Skuse]], English rugby player\n*  1980   &ndash; [[Abby Wambach]], American soccer player and coach\n*  1980   &ndash; [[Tomasz Wr\u00f3blewski]], Polish bass player and songwriter \n*[[1981]] &ndash; [[Nikolay Davydenko]], Russian tennis player\n*  1981   &ndash; [[Chin-hui Tsao]], Taiwanese baseball player\n*[[1982]] &ndash; [[Jewel Staite]], Canadian actress\n*[[1983]] &ndash; [[Chris Higgins (ice hockey)|Chris Higgins]], American ice hockey player\n*  1983   &ndash; [[Leela James]], American singer-songwriter\n*  1983   &ndash; [[Toni Livers]], Swiss skier\n*  1983   &ndash; [[Brooke White]], American singer-songwriter and actress \n*[[1984]] &ndash; [[Jack Afamasaga]], New Zealand rugby league player\n*  1984   &ndash; [[Max Boyer]], Canadian wrestler\n*  1984   &ndash; [[Feleti Mateo]], Australian-Tongan rugby league player\n*[[1985]] &ndash; [[Miyuki Sawashiro]], Japanese voice actress and singer\n*[[1985]] &ndash; [[Maggie Thrash]], American graphic novelist and writer\n*[[1986]] &ndash; [[Todd Carney]], Australian rugby league player\n*[[1987]] &ndash; [[Maryka Holtzhausen]], South African netball player\n*  1987   &ndash; [[Yoann Huget]], French rugby player\n*  1987   &ndash; [[Matthew Koma]], American singer-songwriter and guitarist\n*  1987   &ndash; [[Angelo Mathews]], Sri Lankan cricketer \n*  1987   &ndash; [[Darin Zanyar]], Swedish singer-songwriter\n*  1987   &ndash; [[Sonakshi Sinha]], Indian actress\n*[[1988]] &ndash; [[Sergio Ag\u00fcero]], Argentinian footballer\n*  1988   &ndash; [[Patrik Berglund]], Swedish ice hockey player\n*[[1989]] &ndash; [[Freddy Adu]], Ghanaian-American footballer\n*  1989   &ndash; [[Steve Smith (cricketer)|Steve Smith]], Australian cricketer\n*[[1990]] &ndash; [[Jack Lowden]], Scottish actor\n*[[1992]] &ndash; [[Pajtim Kasami]], Swiss footballer\n*[[1993]] &ndash; [[Adam Taggart]], Australian footballer\n*[[1994]] &ndash; [[Mike Grzesiek]], Esports player and streamer\n*[[1999]] &ndash; [[Campbell Graham]], Australian rugby league player \n*[[2000]] &ndash; [[Lilimar Hernandez]], Venezuelan actress\n<!-- Please do not add yourself, non-notable people, fictional characters, or people without Wikipedia articles to this list. No red links, please. Do not link multiple occurrences of the same year, just link the first occurrence. If there are multiple people in the same birth year, put them in alphabetical order. Do not trust \"this year in history\" websites for accurate date information. -->\n\n==Deaths==\n* [[657]] &ndash; [[Pope Eugene I]]<ref name=\"Thomas1992\">{{cite book|author=P. C. Thomas|title=A Compact History Of The Popes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UYxhI6pq6R4C&pg=PA47|year=1992|publisher=St Pauls BYB|isbn=978-81-7109-142-3|pages=47\u2013}}</ref>\n* [[891]] &ndash; [[Al-Muwaffaq]], Abbasid general (b. 842)\n* [[910]] &ndash; [[Richilde of Provence]] (b. 845)\n*[[1200]] &ndash; Bishop [[John of Oxford]]<ref>{{cite book|title=East Anglian Archaeology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v5hnAAAAMAAJ|year=1987|publisher=Suffolk County Planning D